{"title_page": "GE Dash 9 Series", "text_new": "{{Infobox locomotive\n| name             = GE Dash 9 Series\n| powertype        = Diesel-electric\n| gauge            = {{RailGauge|ussg}}\n| trucks           = GE HiAd\n| image            = GE C44-9W BNSF 4617.jpg\n| caption          = [[BNSF Railway]] [[GE C44-9W]] #4617, at [[Commerce, California]].\n| aarwheels        = C-C (C40-9, C40-9W,<ref name=\"c40-9wtds\">[http://www.thedieselshop.us/DataC40-9W.HTML C40-9W Datasheet], The Diesel Shop</ref> C44-9W,<ref name=\"c44-9wtds\">[http://www.thedieselshop.us/DataC44-9.HTML C44-9W Datasheet], The Diesel Shop</ref> C-38AChe){{br}}B+B-B+B (Dash 9-40BBW)\n| builder=[[General Electric Transportation]]\n| cylindercount    = 16 (C40-9, C40-9W,<ref name=\"c40-9wtds\"/> C44-9W<ref name=\"c44-9wtds\"/>)\n| primemover       = [[GE 7FDL]]16\n| rpmrange=\n| enginetype       = 45\u00b0 [[V16 engine|V16]], [[four stroke cycle]]\n| aspiration       = [[Turbocharged]]\n| displacement     = \n| alternator       = GE \n| tractionmotors   = GE \n| cylindersize     = \n| transmission     = Alternator, silicon diode rectifiers, DC traction motors\n| poweroutput      = {{Convert|4000|hp|abbr=on|lk=in|sigfig=3}} (C40-9, C40-9W, Dash 9-BBW){{br}}{{Convert|4400|hp|abbr=on|lk=in|sigfig=3}} (C44-9W) {{br}}{{Convert|5100|hp|abbr=on|lk=in|sigfig=3}} (C-38AChe)\n| fuelcap          = {{Convert|4600|usgal|l|abbr=on|sigfig=3}} (C40-9, C40-9W<ref name=\"c40-9wtds\"/>){{br}}{{Convert|5300|usgal|l|abbr=on|sigfig=3}} (C44-9W<ref name=\"c44-9wtds\"/>)\n| length           = {{Convert|73|ft|2|in|abbr=on}}\n| totalproduction  =\n| builddate        =\n| nicknames        =\n| operator         = See text\n| disposition      = Most still in service as of 2012.\n| locale           = North America, Australia, Brazil, China}}\n\nThe '''Dash 9 Series''' is a line of [[diesel locomotive]]s built by [[GE Transportation Systems]].  It replaced the [[GE Dash 8 Series|Dash 8 Series]] in the mid-1990s, and was superseded by the [[GE Evolution Series|Evolution Series]] in the mid-2000s. Dash 9 series locomotives are some of the most common in the United States.\n\n==Specifications==\nThe Dash 9 Series is an improved version of the Dash 8 Series.  Like that earlier Series, it has a [[microprocessor]]-equipped [[engine control unit]], and a modular system of construction of the vehicle body.\n\nAll models of the Dash 9 Series are powered by a 16-cylinder, [[turbocharger|turbocharged]], [[GE 7FDL]] 4-stroke diesel engine, with [[electronic fuel injection]] and split cooling.\n\nDash 9 Series locomotives also ride on HiAd high adhesion trucks, with low weight transfer characteristics and microprocessor controlled [[locomotive wheelslip|wheelslip]].\n\n== Six axle models ==\n\n=== Common feature ===\nA specification common to all Dash 9 Series six axle models is the [[AAR wheel arrangement]] known as [[AAR wheel arrangement#C-C|C-C]]\n\n=== C40-9 ===\n[[File:NS 8801 GE C40-9.jpg|thumb|right|180px|NS C40-9 # 8801.]]\n{{main|GE Dash 9-40C}\nthis train is cool\n\nThis version of the Dash 9 was manufactured between January and March 1995.  All 125 examples of this model are owned by the [[Norfolk Southern Railway]].\n\nThe C40-9 is the only model in the Dash 9 Series to feature the standard [[Cab (locomotive)|cab]] design. All were built with rooftop-mounted air conditioners which gives them a rather unusual and distinctive look - and were quickly coined \"top hats\" by the railfan community. Other than the standard cab, the model is identical in all specifications to the wide-nose [[Canadian comfort cab|\"North American\" safety cab]] Dash 9-40CW (or C40-9W) model (see below).\n\nNS specifically requested the standard cab, and may have purchased more units had the [[Federal Railroad Administration]] not required it to purchase the wide-nose C40-9W version instead.<ref name=americanrails_c409w>{{cite web|title=The GE C40-9/W|url=http://www.american-rails.com/ge-c40-9.html|work=American-Rails.com|accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref> Besides, standard cab GE's had become more expensive by the mid-1990s, since they were now considered optional equipment by the builder, and thus priced as such, and when a carrier is purchasing one or two hundred units of a particular model at a time, even a slight extra price for a customized cab can add hundreds of thousands of dollars to the cost of a locomotive order.\n\nIn 2015, the railroad announced the locomotives would be given a new wide cab, A.C. traction motors, cab signals, LSL and uprated to 4400 HP. The new locomotives will be designated as [[GE AC44C6M|AC44C6M]]. The last of the \"top hats\" were rebuilt to AC44C6M's in November 2018.\n\n* Power output: {{Convert|4000|hp|abbr=on|lk=in|sigfig=3}}\n\n=== C40-9W ===\n[[File:Norfolk Southern C40-9W -9258 (locomotif)IMG 1970.jpg|thumb|right|180px|NS C40-9W # 9258.]]\n{{main|GE Dash 9-40CW}}\n\nAll 1,090 units of this model were built for the Norfolk Southern Railway, as road numbers 8889 to 9978.\n\nThe orders for these units were basically an extension of NS's previous order for the standard cab Dash 9-40C (or C40-9) (see above).\n\nThey were built under the same premise that a lower power rating than the {{convert|4400|hp|kW|abbr=on}} rating of the Dash 9-44CW (or C44-9W) (see below) would prolong the life of the engine, and use less fuel.\n\nHowever, there is a manual override switch that allows the [[railroad engineer|engineer]] to run the engine with all {{convert|4400|hp|kW|abbr=on}} if necessary.\n\nAs with the C40-9, Norfolk Southern began to upgrade their C40-9W's from 4,000 to 4,400&nbsp;hp and AC traction in mid-2015, making them AC44C6M's as well. Others will be rebuilt as the AC44C6CF.\n\n* Power output: {{Convert|4000|hp|abbr=on|lk=in|sigfig=3}}\n\n=== C44-9W ===\n[[File:Brockman 4 train 2.JPG|thumb|right|180px|[[Hamersley & Robe River railway|Hamersley Iron]] C44-9W # 7072 at the [[Brockman 4 mine]].]]\n{{main|GE Dash 9-44CW}}\n\nThe C44-9W model was in production between 1993 and 2004 with 53 pre-production units being built for CSX with an extended Dash 8 carbody and trucks a couple years earlier.\n\nOf all the Dash 9 Series models, this one received by far the greatest number of orders.\n\nA total of 1,697 orders for C44-9W's were received from [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway]] and successor [[BNSF Railway]] (known at the time as the Burlington Northern Santa Fe Railway).\n\nOther large orders from North American operators were placed by [[Canadian National Railway]] and a number of operators that have since been absorbed by the present day [[Union Pacific Railroad]], including [[Chicago and Northwestern]] and [[Southern Pacific]].\n\nSubstantial orders for this model were also received from operators in Australia and Brazil, in the latter case for {{RailGauge|1600mm}} broad gauge versions.\n\nGeneral Electric and Norfolk Southern agreed to rebuild 450 of these C44-9W's, making them AC44C6M's along with their C40-9's and C40-9W's. Norfolk Southern is essentially converting all of their Dash 9 units into AC44C6M's.\n\n* Power output: {{Convert|4400|hp|abbr=on|lk=in|sigfig=3}}\n\n=== C-38AChe ===\n[[File:China Railways NJ2 0053.jpg|thumb|right|180px|[[China Railway]] NJ2 0053.]]\n{{main|China Railways NJ2}}\n\nThe C-38AChe, also known as the NJ2, is operated by [[China Railway]].\n\nBuilt in [[Erie, Pennsylvania]], it is based on a standard Dash 9-44CW (or C44-9W) (see above) and marketed as the GE C38AChe.\n\nThe model was specially customised for high altitude operation on the [[Qinghai-Tibet Railway]] route.\n\nIt is used on the [[Qingzang Railway]], which connects [[Xining]], [[Qinghai|Qinghai Province]], to [[Lhasa]], [[Tibet Autonomous Region]], in the [[People's Republic of China]].\n\n* Power output: {{Convert|5100|hp|abbr=on|lk=in|sigfig=3}}\n\n==Eight axle model==\n\n=== DASH 9-40BBW ===\n\nThis is a {{RailGauge|1000mm}} ([[meter gauge]]) version of the C40-9W.  It was manufactured between 1997 and 2006.\n\nAll 141 examples of the model are owned by the [[Estrada de Ferro Vit\u00f3ria a Minas]]<ref>See [[:pt:Estrada de Ferro Vit\u00f3ria a Minas]] {{in lang|pt}}.</ref> (EFVM), a railroad in Brazil.\n\nThe model is equipped with four B-style trucks, two at each end, replacing the conventional C-style trucks. The different trucks are necessary due to the railroad load limit per axle, which is 25 metric tons (\u00b155,156&nbsp;lbs).\n\nThe standard C40-9W traction motors cannot fit in the narrower trucks. To achieve the same total power, more of the smaller traction motors are needed.\n\n* Power output: {{Convert|4000|hp|abbr=on|lk=in|sigfig=3}}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Trains}}\n*[[List of GE locomotives]]\n*[[National Rail NR class|NR class locomotives]]\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Lamb-Evolution}}\n* {{McDonnell-Locomotives}}\n* {{Solomon-American Diesel}}\n* {{Solomon-GE Locomotives}}\n* {{Solomon-Modern Locomotives}}\n* {{Solomon-Modern Diesel}}\n* {{Solomon-North American Locomotives}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* GE Transportation Systems. ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20100928155720/http://www.getransportation.com/rail/rail-products/locomotives/earlier-locomotive-models.html Earlier Locomotive Models]'' \u2013 includes the Dash 9 Series\n* NorthEast Rails: ''[http://www.northeast.railfan.net/diesel39.html GE Dash9 39-44 Diesel Railroad Locomotives]''\n\n''This article is based upon a translation of the [[:ja:GE Dash 9\u30b7\u30ea\u30fc\u30ba\u30c7\u30a3\u30fc\u30bc\u30eb\u6a5f\u95a2\u8eca|Japanese language version]] as at August 2012.''\n<br>\n{{GE diesels}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ge Dash 9 Series}}\n[[Category:General Electric locomotives|Dash 9 Series]]\n[[Category:C-C locomotives]]\n[[Category:Diesel-electric locomotives of the United States]]\n[[Category:B+B-B+B locomotives]]\n[[Category:Railway locomotives introduced in 1993]]\n[[Category:Standard gauge locomotives of Canada]]\n[[Category:Standard gauge locomotives of the United States]]\n[[Category:Standard gauge locomotives of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Diesel-electric locomotives of Canada]]\n[[Category:Diesel-electric locomotives of Mexico]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox locomotive\n| name             = GE Dash 9 Series\n| powertype        = Diesel-electric\n| gauge            = {{RailGauge|ussg}}\n| trucks           = GE HiAd\n| image            = GE C44-9W BNSF 4617.jpg\n| caption          = [[BNSF Railway]] [[GE C44-9W]] #4617, at [[Commerce, California]].\n| aarwheels        = C-C (C40-9, C40-9W,<ref name=\"c40-9wtds\">[http://www.thedieselshop.us/DataC40-9W.HTML C40-9W Datasheet], The Diesel Shop</ref> C44-9W,<ref name=\"c44-9wtds\">[http://www.thedieselshop.us/DataC44-9.HTML C44-9W Datasheet], The Diesel Shop</ref> C-38AChe){{br}}B+B-B+B (Dash 9-40BBW)\n| builder=[[General Electric Transportation]]\n| cylindercount    = 16 (C40-9, C40-9W,<ref name=\"c40-9wtds\"/> C44-9W<ref name=\"c44-9wtds\"/>)\n| primemover       = [[GE 7FDL]]16\n| rpmrange=\n| enginetype       = 45\u00b0 [[V16 engine|V16]], [[four stroke cycle]]\n| aspiration       = [[Turbocharged]]\n| displacement     = \n| alternator       = GE \n| tractionmotors   = GE \n| cylindersize     = \n| transmission     = Alternator, silicon diode rectifiers, DC traction motors\n| poweroutput      = {{Convert|4000|hp|abbr=on|lk=in|sigfig=3}} (C40-9, C40-9W, Dash 9-BBW){{br}}{{Convert|4400|hp|abbr=on|lk=in|sigfig=3}} (C44-9W) {{br}}{{Convert|5100|hp|abbr=on|lk=in|sigfig=3}} (C-38AChe)\n| fuelcap          = {{Convert|4600|usgal|l|abbr=on|sigfig=3}} (C40-9, C40-9W<ref name=\"c40-9wtds\"/>){{br}}{{Convert|5300|usgal|l|abbr=on|sigfig=3}} (C44-9W<ref name=\"c44-9wtds\"/>)\n| length           = {{Convert|73|ft|2|in|abbr=on}}\n| totalproduction  =\n| builddate        =\n| nicknames        =\n| operator         = See text\n| disposition      = Most still in service as of 2012.\n| locale           = North America, Australia, Brazil, China}}\n\nThe '''Dash 9 Series''' is a line of [[diesel locomotive]]s built by [[GE Transportation Systems]].  It replaced the [[GE Dash 8 Series|Dash 8 Series]] in the mid-1990s, and was superseded by the [[GE Evolution Series|Evolution Series]] in the mid-2000s. Dash 9 series locomotives are some of the most common in the United States.\n\n==Specifications==\nThe Dash 9 Series is an improved version of the Dash 8 Series.  Like that earlier Series, it has a [[microprocessor]]-equipped [[engine control unit]], and a modular system of construction of the vehicle body.\n\nAll models of the Dash 9 Series are powered by a 16-cylinder, [[turbocharger|turbocharged]], [[GE 7FDL]] 4-stroke diesel engine, with [[electronic fuel injection]] and split cooling.\n\nDash 9 Series locomotives also ride on HiAd high adhesion trucks, with low weight transfer characteristics and microprocessor controlled [[locomotive wheelslip|wheelslip]].\n\n== Six axle models ==\n\n=== Common feature ===\nA specification common to all Dash 9 Series six axle models is the [[AAR wheel arrangement]] known as [[AAR wheel arrangement#C-C|C-C]]\n\n=== C40-9 ===\n[[File:NS 8801 GE C40-9.jpg|thumb|right|180px|NS C40-9 # 8801.]]\n{{main|GE Dash 9-40C}}\n\nThis version of the Dash 9 was manufactured between January and March 1995.  All 125 examples of this model are owned by the [[Norfolk Southern Railway]].\n\nThe C40-9 is the only model in the Dash 9 Series to feature the standard [[Cab (locomotive)|cab]] design. All were built with rooftop-mounted air conditioners which gives them a rather unusual and distinctive look - and were quickly coined \"top hats\" by the railfan community. Other than the standard cab, the model is identical in all specifications to the wide-nose [[Canadian comfort cab|\"North American\" safety cab]] Dash 9-40CW (or C40-9W) model (see below).\n\nNS specifically requested the standard cab, and may have purchased more units had the [[Federal Railroad Administration]] not required it to purchase the wide-nose C40-9W version instead.<ref name=americanrails_c409w>{{cite web|title=The GE C40-9/W|url=http://www.american-rails.com/ge-c40-9.html|work=American-Rails.com|accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref> Besides, standard cab GE's had become more expensive by the mid-1990s, since they were now considered optional equipment by the builder, and thus priced as such, and when a carrier is purchasing one or two hundred units of a particular model at a time, even a slight extra price for a customized cab can add hundreds of thousands of dollars to the cost of a locomotive order.\n\nIn 2015, the railroad announced the locomotives would be given a new wide cab, A.C. traction motors, cab signals, LSL and uprated to 4400 HP. The new locomotives will be designated as [[GE AC44C6M|AC44C6M]]. The last of the \"top hats\" were rebuilt to AC44C6M's in November 2018.\n\n* Power output: {{Convert|4000|hp|abbr=on|lk=in|sigfig=3}}\n\n=== C40-9W ===\n[[File:Norfolk Southern C40-9W -9258 (locomotif)IMG 1970.jpg|thumb|right|180px|NS C40-9W # 9258.]]\n{{main|GE Dash 9-40CW}}\n\nAll 1,090 units of this model were built for the Norfolk Southern Railway, as road numbers 8889 to 9978.\n\nThe orders for these units were basically an extension of NS's previous order for the standard cab Dash 9-40C (or C40-9) (see above).\n\nThey were built under the same premise that a lower power rating than the {{convert|4400|hp|kW|abbr=on}} rating of the Dash 9-44CW (or C44-9W) (see below) would prolong the life of the engine, and use less fuel.\n\nHowever, there is a manual override switch that allows the [[railroad engineer|engineer]] to run the engine with all {{convert|4400|hp|kW|abbr=on}} if necessary.\n\nAs with the C40-9, Norfolk Southern began to upgrade their C40-9W's from 4,000 to 4,400&nbsp;hp and AC traction in mid-2015, making them AC44C6M's as well. Others will be rebuilt as the AC44C6CF.\n\n* Power output: {{Convert|4000|hp|abbr=on|lk=in|sigfig=3}}\n\n=== C44-9W ===\n[[File:Brockman 4 train 2.JPG|thumb|right|180px|[[Hamersley & Robe River railway|Hamersley Iron]] C44-9W # 7072 at the [[Brockman 4 mine]].]]\n{{main|GE Dash 9-44CW}}\n\nThe C44-9W model was in production between 1993 and 2004 with 53 pre-production units being built for CSX with an extended Dash 8 carbody and trucks a couple years earlier.\n\nOf all the Dash 9 Series models, this one received by far the greatest number of orders.\n\nA total of 1,697 orders for C44-9W's were received from [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway]] and successor [[BNSF Railway]] (known at the time as the Burlington Northern Santa Fe Railway).\n\nOther large orders from North American operators were placed by [[Canadian National Railway]] and a number of operators that have since been absorbed by the present day [[Union Pacific Railroad]], including [[Chicago and Northwestern]] and [[Southern Pacific]].\n\nSubstantial orders for this model were also received from operators in Australia and Brazil, in the latter case for {{RailGauge|1600mm}} broad gauge versions.\n\nGeneral Electric and Norfolk Southern agreed to rebuild 450 of these C44-9W's, making them AC44C6M's along with their C40-9's and C40-9W's. Norfolk Southern is essentially converting all of their Dash 9 units into AC44C6M's.\n\n* Power output: {{Convert|4400|hp|abbr=on|lk=in|sigfig=3}}\n\n=== C-38AChe ===\n[[File:China Railways NJ2 0053.jpg|thumb|right|180px|[[China Railway]] NJ2 0053.]]\n{{main|China Railways NJ2}}\n\nThe C-38AChe, also known as the NJ2, is operated by [[China Railway]].\n\nBuilt in [[Erie, Pennsylvania]], it is based on a standard Dash 9-44CW (or C44-9W) (see above) and marketed as the GE C38AChe.\n\nThe model was specially customised for high altitude operation on the [[Qinghai-Tibet Railway]] route.\n\nIt is used on the [[Qingzang Railway]], which connects [[Xining]], [[Qinghai|Qinghai Province]], to [[Lhasa]], [[Tibet Autonomous Region]], in the [[People's Republic of China]].\n\n* Power output: {{Convert|5100|hp|abbr=on|lk=in|sigfig=3}}\n\n==Eight axle model==\n\n=== DASH 9-40BBW ===\n\nThis is a {{RailGauge|1000mm}} ([[meter gauge]]) version of the C40-9W.  It was manufactured between 1997 and 2006.\n\nAll 141 examples of the model are owned by the [[Estrada de Ferro Vit\u00f3ria a Minas]]<ref>See [[:pt:Estrada de Ferro Vit\u00f3ria a Minas]] {{in lang|pt}}.</ref> (EFVM), a railroad in Brazil.\n\nThe model is equipped with four B-style trucks, two at each end, replacing the conventional C-style trucks. The different trucks are necessary due to the railroad load limit per axle, which is 25 metric tons (\u00b155,156&nbsp;lbs).\n\nThe standard C40-9W traction motors cannot fit in the narrower trucks. To achieve the same total power, more of the smaller traction motors are needed.\n\n* Power output: {{Convert|4000|hp|abbr=on|lk=in|sigfig=3}}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Trains}}\n*[[List of GE locomotives]]\n*[[National Rail NR class|NR class locomotives]]\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Lamb-Evolution}}\n* {{McDonnell-Locomotives}}\n* {{Solomon-American Diesel}}\n* {{Solomon-GE Locomotives}}\n* {{Solomon-Modern Locomotives}}\n* {{Solomon-Modern Diesel}}\n* {{Solomon-North American Locomotives}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* GE Transportation Systems. ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20100928155720/http://www.getransportation.com/rail/rail-products/locomotives/earlier-locomotive-models.html Earlier Locomotive Models]'' \u2013 includes the Dash 9 Series\n* NorthEast Rails: ''[http://www.northeast.railfan.net/diesel39.html GE Dash9 39-44 Diesel Railroad Locomotives]''\n\n''This article is based upon a translation of the [[:ja:GE Dash 9\u30b7\u30ea\u30fc\u30ba\u30c7\u30a3\u30fc\u30bc\u30eb\u6a5f\u95a2\u8eca|Japanese language version]] as at August 2012.''\n<br>\n{{GE diesels}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ge Dash 9 Series}}\n[[Category:General Electric locomotives|Dash 9 Series]]\n[[Category:C-C locomotives]]\n[[Category:Diesel-electric lo