ta a Asturias]]\n::1st Stage 1 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]])\n: 1st [[File:Jersey blue.svg|20px]] Overall [[Euskal Bizikleta]]\n::1st Stage 5\n: 2nd Overall [[Vuelta a Burgos]]\n{{colend}}\n\n=== Grand Tour general classification results timeline ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Grand Tour (cycling)|Grand Tour]]\n! scope=\"col\" | 1985\n! scope=\"col\" | 1986\n! scope=\"col\" | 1987\n! scope=\"col\" | 1988\n! scope=\"col\" | 1989\n! scope=\"col\" | 1990\n! scope=\"col\" | 1991\n! scope=\"col\" | 1992\n! scope=\"col\" | 1993\n! scope=\"col\" | 1994\n! scope=\"col\" | 1995\n! scope=\"col\" | 1996\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\" | [[File:Jersey pink.svg|20px|link=|alt=A pink jersey]] [[General classification in the Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]]\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|bgcolor=pink|'''[[1992 Giro d'Italia|1]]'''\n|bgcolor=pink|'''[[1993 Giro d'Italia|1]]'''\n|style=\"background:#ddf;\"| [[1994 Giro d'Italia|'''3''']]\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\" | [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px|link=|alt=A yellow jersey]] [[General classification in the Tour de France|Tour de France]]\n|[[1985 Tour de France|DNF]]\n|[[1986 Tour de France|DNF]]\n|[[1987 Tour de France|97]]\n|[[1988 Tour de France|47]]\n|[[1989 Tour de France|17]]\n|style=\"background:#ddf;\"|[[1990 Tour de France|10]]\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"|'''[[1991 Tour de France|1]]'''\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"|'''[[1992 Tour de France|1]]'''\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"|'''[[1993 Tour de France|1]]'''\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"|'''[[1994 Tour de France|1]]'''\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"|'''[[1995 Tour de France|1]]'''\n|[[1996 Tour de France|11]]\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\" | [[File:Jersey gold.svg|20px|link=|alt=A gold jersey]] [[List of Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a general classification winners|Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]]\n|[[1985 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|84]]\n|[[1986 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|92]]\n|[[1987 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|DNF]]\n|[[1988 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|DNF]]\n|[[1989 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|DNF]]\n|style=\"background:#ddf;\"|[[1990 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|7]]\n|style=\"background:#ddf;\"|'''[[1991 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|2]]'''\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|[[1996 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|DNF]]\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Legend\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \u2014\n| Did not compete\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Did Not Finish|DNF]]\n| Did not finish\n|}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=\"N\"}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|22em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book | last=Abt | first=Samuel | authorlink=Samuel Abt | others=Translated by Jeremy Munday | title=Champion: Bicycle Racing in the Age of Miguel Indur\u00e1in | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6Mz-OQAACAAJ | year=1993 | publisher=Bicycle Books | location=San Francisco | isbn=978-0-933201-59-0 }}\n* {{cite book | last=S\u00e1nchez | first=Javier Garc\u00eda | title=Indur\u00e1in: A Tempered Passion | url=https://archive.org/details/induraintempered0000garc | year=2002 | publisher=Mousehold Press | location=Norwich, UK | isbn=978-1-874739-23-4 | url-access=registration }}\n*{{cite journal |vauthors=Mujika I |title=The cycling physiology of Miguel Indur\u00e1in 14 years after retirement |journal=International Journal of Sports Physiology and Performance |volume=7 |issue=4 |pages=397\u2013400 |year=2012 |pmid=22868823 }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Miguel Indur\u00e1in}}\n* [http://www.fundacionmiguelindurain.com/ Miguel Indur\u00e1in's Foundation]\n* [http://atlanta1996.coe.es/ Spanish Olympic Committee]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{Succession box|before={{flagicon|UKR}} [[Sergey Bubka]]|title=[[Prince of Asturias Award#Sports|Prince of Asturias Award for Sports]]|years=1992|after={{flagicon|CUB}} [[Javier Sotomayor]]}}\n{{succession box\n| before=[[Kevin Young (athlete)|Kevin Young]] |\n| title=[[United Press International Athlete of the Year Award#Male winners|United Press International<br />Athlete of the Year]] |\n| after=[[Johan Olav Koss]] |\n| years=1993}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{giro d'Italia general classification winners}}\n{{Tour de France general classification winners}}\n{{V\u00e9lo d'Or}}\n{{Footer olympic champions time trial men}}\n{{UCI Road World Champions&nbsp;\u2013 Men's time trial}}\n{{Spanish Sportsman of the Year}}\n{{UCI Hall of Fame}}\n{{Prince of Asturias Award for Sports}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Indur\u00e1in, Miguel}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia cyclists]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia winners]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1984 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Navarrese cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Spain]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for Spain]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in cycling]]\n[[Category:People from Cuenca de Pamplona]]\n[[Category:Spanish male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Spanish Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Spanish Tour de France stage winners]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n[[Category:Tour de France prologue winners]]\n[[Category:Tour de France winners]]\n[[Category:UCI Road World Champions (elite men)]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia and Tour de France winners in the same year]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Pamplona]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Spanish cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{Spanish name|Indur\u00e1in|Larraya}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Miguel Indur\u00e1in\n| image          = Miguel Indurain en la Vuelta a Castilla y Le\u00f3n 2009 (cropped).jpg\n| caption        = Indur\u00e1in in 2009\n| fullname       = Miguel Indur\u00e1in Larraya\n| nickname       = Miguel\u00f3n, Big Mig (English)\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1964|7|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Villava]], [[Navarre]], Spain<ref name=autogenerated10>''L'\u00c9quipe'', France, 15 July 2000</ref>\n| height         = {{height|m=1.86}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://premierendurance.ie/the-cycling-physiology-of-miguel-indurain-14-years-after-retirement/|title=The Cycling Physiology of Miguel Indurain 14 Years After Retirement|accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref>\n| weight         = {{convert|76|kg|lb stlb|0|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/07/21/sports/IHT-prudencio-and-miguel-indurain-cycling-brothers-just-alike-except-.html|title=Prudencio and Miguel Indurain: Cycling Brothers Just Alike, Except. . .|accessdate=25 October 2019}}</ref>\n| currentteam    = Retired\n| discipline     = Road\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = All-rounder\n| amateuryears1  = 1978\u20131983\n| amateurteam1   = CC Villav\u00e9s\n| proyears1      = 1984\u20131996\n| proteam1       = {{ct|MOV|1984}}\n| majorwins      = '''[[Grand Tour]]'''\n:'''[[Tour de France]]'''\n::'''[[General classification in the Tour de France|General classification]]''' ([[1991 Tour de France|1991]], [[1992 Tour de France|1992]], [[1993 Tour de France|1993]], [[1994 Tour de France|1994]], [[1995 Tour de France|1995]])\n::12 individual stages ([[1989 Tour de France|1989]]\u2013[[1995 Tour de France|1995]])\n:'''[[Giro d'Italia]]'''\n::'''[[General classification in the Giro d'Italia|General classification]]''' ([[1992 Giro d'Italia|1992]], [[1993 Giro d'Italia|1993]])\n::[[Intergiro classification in the Giro d'Italia|Intergiro classification]] ([[1992 Giro d'Italia|1992]])\n::4 individual stages ([[1992 Giro d'Italia|1992]], [[1993 Giro d'Italia|1993]])\n'''[[Race stage|Stage races]]'''\n:[[Volta a Catalunya]] (1988, 1991, 1992)\n:[[Paris\u2013Nice]] (1989, 1990)\n:[[Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9]] (1995, 1996)\n:[[Crit\u00e9rium International]] (1991)\n:[[Grand Prix du Midi Libre]] (1995)\n'''[[Classic cycle races|One-day races and Classics]]'''\n:[[UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Men's time trial|World Time Trial Championships]] ([[1995 UCI Road World Championships&nbsp;\u2013 Men's time trial|1995]])\n:{{nowrap|[[Spanish National Road Race Championships|National Road Race Championships]] (1992)}}\n:[[Cl\u00e1sica de San Sebasti\u00e1n]] (1990)\n'''Other'''\n:[[Hour record]] 53.040 km (2 September 1994)\n| show-medals    = no\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalCountry|Spain}}\n{{MedalSport |Men's [[road bicycle racing]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1996 Summer Olympics|1996 Atlanta]]|[[Cycling at the 1996 Summer Olympics&nbsp;\u2013 Men's time trial|Time trial]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|World Championships}}\n{{MedalGold |[[1995 UCI Road World Championships|1995 Duitama]]|Elite time trial}}\n{{MedalSilver |[[1993 UCI Road World Championships|1993 Oslo]]|Elite road race}}\n{{MedalSilver |[[1995 UCI Road World Championships|1995 Duitama]]|Elite road race}}\n{{MedalBronze |[[1991 UCI Road World Championships|1991 Stuttgart]]|Elite road race}}\n}}\n\n'''Miguel Indur\u00e1in Larraya''' ({{IPA-es|mi\u02c8\u0263el indu\u02c8\u027eain la\u02c8ra\u029da}}; born 16 July 1964) is a retired Spanish [[road racing cyclist]]. Indur\u00e1in won five [[Tours de France]] from [[1991 Tour de France|1991]] to [[1995 Tour de France|1995]], the fourth, and last, to win five times, and the only five-time winner to achieve those victories consecutively.<ref name=\"autogenerated9\" /> \n\nHe won the [[Giro d'Italia]] twice, becoming one of seven people to achieve the Giro-Tour double in the same season. He wore the race leader's yellow jersey in the Tour de France for 60 days.<ref name=\"autogenerated10\" /> Since the revoking of [[Lance Armstrong]]'s seven wins, he now holds the record for the most consecutive Tour de France wins and shares the record for most wins with [[Jacques Anquetil]], [[Bernard Hinault]] and [[Eddy Merckx]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/in/miguel-indurain-1.html |title=Miguel Indur\u00e1in Olympic Results |accessdate=18 May 2015 |work=Sports Reference}}</ref> He is the most recent cyclist, and one of the very few cyclists, to have come close to cycling's 'Triple Crown' when in [[1993 UCI Road World Championships | 1993]], after having already won the Giro and the Tour, he finished just 0:19 behind in the World Championship.\n\nIndur\u00e1in's ability and physical size\u2014{{convert|1.86|m|ftin|abbr=on}} and {{convert|76|kg|lbs|sigfig=3}}\u2014earned him the nickname \"Miguel\u00f3n\" or \"Big Mig\". He was the youngest rider ever to win the Spanish amateur national road championship, when he was 18,<ref name=\"autogenerated6\">L'\u00c9quipe, France, 8 July 2001</ref> at 20 the youngest rider to lead the [[Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]],<ref name=\"autogenerated6\" /> and at 20 he won a stage of the [[Tour de l'Avenir]].<ref name=\"autogenerated6\" /><ref name=\"autogenerated2\" />\n\n== Early life and amateur career ==\nMiguel Indur\u00e1in was born in the village of Villava (now Villava&nbsp;\u2013 Atarrabia), which is now an outlying area of [[Pamplona]]. He has three sisters&nbsp;\u2013 Isabel, Mar\u00eda Dolores and Mar\u00eda Asunci\u00f3n<ref name=autogenerated5>Het Volk, Belgium, 31 December 1991</ref>&nbsp;\u2013 and a brother, [[Prudencio Indur\u00e1in|Prudencio]], who also became a professional cyclist.<ref name=autogenerated1>Cycling Weekly, UK, undated cutting</ref> His first bicycle was a green secondhand Olmo given to him for his 10th birthday. It was stolen when he was 11 and he worked in the fields with his father to pay for a new one.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\nIndur\u00e1in tried running, basketball, javelin and football from nine to 14. Then he joined the local CC Villav\u00e9s and rode his first race in July 1978,<ref name=\"autogenerated6\" /><ref group=\"N\">L'\u00c9quipe reported on 8 July 2001 that 2,000 children had taken up cycling in the town because of Indur\u00e1in's fame.</ref> an event for unlicensed riders in which he finished second.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> He won his second race and competed every week thereafter.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> His hero in cycling was [[Bernard Hinault]].<ref>Cycling Weekly, UK, 9 February 2002</ref> At 18 he was the youngest winner of the national amateur road championship.<ref name=\"autogenerated6\" />\n\n== Professional career ==\nIn 1984 he rode in the Olympic Games at Los Angeles and then turned professional on 4 September<ref name=autogenerated6 /> for {{ct|MOV|1984}}.<ref name=autogenerated10 /><ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/palmares/indurain_miguel.php |title=Palmar\u00e8s de Miguel Indur\u00e1in |publisher=Memoire du Cyclisme |accessdate=16 November 2010 |language=French |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110311044743/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/palmares/indurain_miguel.php |archivedate=11 March 2011 }}</ref> He won his first professional race a week later, a time trial in the [[Tour de l'Avenir]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.elmundodeportivo.es/preview/1984/09/16/pagina-33/1455598/pdf.html|title=Indur\u00e1in venci\u00f3 la contrarreloj |language=Spanish|page=33|date=16 September 1984|accessdate=16 November 2010|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo}}</ref> In 1985 he started the [[1985 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]] and came second in the prologue, behind [[Bert Oosterbosch]]. Oosterbosch lost time on the second stage and Indur\u00e1in became leader, the youngest rider to do so.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.elmundodeportivo.es/preview/1985/04/26/pagina-29/1123992/pdf.html|page=29|title=Indur\u00e1in: Ser l\u00edder a los 20 a\u00f1os|language=Spanish|date=26 April 1985|accessdate=16 November 2010|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo}}</ref> He rode the [[Tour de France]] later that year, as he would do in each of the next 11 years, but dropped out in the fourth stage.<ref name=\"letour\">{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/coureur/4719.html|title=The Tour&nbsp;\u2013 Miguel Indur\u00e1in|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=16 November 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100716175259/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/coureur/4719.html|archive-date=16 July 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986, Indur\u00e1in again rode the Tour, dropping out on the 12th stage.<ref name=\"letour\" /> He started the [[1987 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]] with bronchitis from the Tour of Belgium.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.elmundodeportivo.es/preview/1987/03/24/pagina-38/1154199/pdf.html|title=Indur\u00e1in emperaza con bronquitis|page=38|language=Spanish|date=24 March 1987|accessdate=16 November 2010|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo}}</ref> He rode the [[1988 Tour de France]] as teammate of the winner [[Pedro Delgado]]. In 1989, he escaped during the ninth stage of the Tour de France. He won the stage and became leader of the [[Mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]], wearing the polkadot jersey the next stage, the only time in his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/archive/382984/1989-how-it-happened.html|title=1989 How it happened|date=14 July 2009|publisher=Cycling weekly}}</ref> In 1990, Indur\u00e1in rode the Tour de France again for Delgado, but Delgado could not win. Indur\u00e1in finished 10th place, sacrificing several places by waiting for Delgado.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/cycling/tour_de_france_2004/history/3772501.stm|title=1991\u20131995: Big Mig's masterclass|work=BBC Sport |date=3 August 2004|accessdate=16 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nIndur\u00e1in was a strong [[Individual time trial|time trialist]], gaining on rivals and riding defensively in the climbing stages. Indur\u00e1in won only two Tour stages that were not [[individual time trial]]s: mountain stages to [[Cauterets]] (1989) and [[Luz Ardiden]] (1990) in the [[Pyrenees]]. During his five consecutive Tour de France wins he never won a stage that was not a time trial. These superior abilities in the discipline fit perfectly with the TT heavy Tours of the era, with many featuring between 150 and 200&nbsp;km of time trialling vs the more common 50\u201380&nbsp;km today.\n\n=== 1991: First Tour win ===\n[[File:Miguel Indurain Iberia.jpg|thumb|left|Indur\u00e1in with the trophy won at the [[1991 Tour de France]]]]\nIn 1991, [[Greg LeMond]] was favourite for the Tour and while Indur\u00e1in was a fine time trialist he was considered too large to be a good climber.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SqGuMRheyWUC&pg=PA32|title=The complete idiot's guide to cycling|author=Armijo, Vic|publisher=Penguin|year=1999|isbn=0-02-862929-9}}</ref> LeMond led the race until the 12th stage but on the 13th he broke down on the Tourmalet,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1978_2005/tdf1991.php|title=78\u00e8me Tour de France 1991|publisher=Memoire du Cyclisme|language=French|accessdate=16 November 2010}}</ref> and lost more than seven minutes to Indur\u00e1in, who became the leader and stayed leader to the end.\n\n=== 1992: Tour-Giro double ===\nIndur\u00e1in won the prologue at [[San Sebasti\u00e1n]] and seized the yellow jersey, only to lose it the next day. Indur\u00e1in finished the time trial in stage nine, over 65&nbsp;km, three minutes ahead of number two on the stage. Near the end he caught [[Laurent Fignon]], who had started six minutes before him. The [[1992 Tour de France|1992 Tour]] was remarkable for a long breakaway by [[Claudio Chiappucci]] on a stage to [[Sestriere]] that included six mountains. Indur\u00e1in seemed to crack on the final climb to Sestriere being passed by [[Franco Vona]] but managed to finish third, enough to claim the yellow jersey once more. From here Indur\u00e1in would establish his racing style \"crush rivals in the time trails and control them in the mountains\"<ref>Cossins, Peter; Best, Isabel; Sidwells, Chris; Griffith, Clare (2013). ''Le Tour 100: The definitive history of the world's greatest race''. London: Octopus Publishing Group Limited. pp.182-183 . {{ISBN|978-1-84403-723-0}}.</ref>  His defensive tactic brought criticism from Indur\u00e1in's boyhood hero, Bernard Hinault, who said: \"Indur\u00e1in is the best rider of his generation but he has won this Tour quietly, without great opposition. If the opposition continues to let him get away with it, his reign looks like lasting a long time\".<ref name=\"Ollivier81\">Ollivier, Jean-Paul (1999), Maillot Jaune, S\u00e9lection du Readers Digest, France, p81, {{ISBN|978-2-7098-1091-3}}</ref>\n\nHe also won the [[Giro d'Italia]] in 1992. After winning the early time trial, Indur\u00e1in gained a decisive advantage on stage 9 to Latina-Terminillo. There, on the first summit finish of the race, Indur\u00e1in finished in the first group, dropping the main contenders, and gaining 30 seconds on Chiappucci.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/grand-tour-doubles-miguel-indurain-849|title=Grand Tour Doubles \u2013 Miguel Indur\u00e1in \u2013 Cycling Weekly|date=24 September 2010|publisher=}}</ref> On his way to overall victory by 5mins 12secs over Chiapucci, Indur\u00e1in also won the final stage 21 time trial.\n\n=== 1993: Second Tour-Giro double ===\n[[File:Miguel INDURAIN (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Indur\u00e1in at the [[1993 Tour de France]]]]\nIndur\u00e1in rode the same way in the [[1993 Tour de France|1993 Tour]]. He won the prologue at Puy-du-Fou, in the Vend\u00e9e region, and waited until the ninth stage, the 59&nbsp;km time trial at Lac de Madine, to take control of the race. He won by 2&nbsp;m 11s.<ref name=\"Ollivier81\" /> From then on, said Ollivier, he rode defensively, watching [[Tony Rominger]], whom he considered a rival against the clock.<ref name=\"Ollivier81\" /> Ollivier said Indur\u00e1in's ride wasn't without effort but another historian, [[Pierre Chany]], said it lacked audacity and that Indur\u00e1in never \"did anything unprovoked which would have allowed this exceptional rider to rise above the rest and excite the crowd\".<ref name=\"Ollivier81\" />\n\nHe won the [[1993 Giro d'Italia]].<ref name=autogenerated10 />\n\n=== 1994: Tour and hour record ===\n[[Image:MaillotAmarilloIndur\u00e1in95.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Indur\u00e1in's yellow jersey, [[1995 Tour de France]].]]\nIndur\u00e1in again won the first time trial, the ninth stage from [[P\u00e9rigueux]] to Bergerac, in the south-west. He beat Rominger by two minutes. He did, however, attack in the [[Pyrenees]], accelerating at the foot of the 10&nbsp;km climb to the ski station at [[Hautacam]]. [[Luc Leblanc]], [[Richard Virenque]], [[Marco Pantani]] and Armand de Las Cuevas stayed with him but other rivals, including Rominger, were left behind. Indur\u00e1in lost the stage to Leblanc but kept the yellow jersey to the end.\n\nIn 1994 he set a world [[hour record]] of {{convert|53.040|km|mi}},<ref name=autogenerated10 /> beating [[Graeme Obree]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Padilla |first1=S |last2=Mujika |first2=I | last3=Angulo |first3= F|last4= Goiriena |first4=JJ |year=2000 |title=Scientific approach to the 1-h cycling world record: a case study. |journal=[[Journal of Applied Physiology]] |publisher=American Physiological Society |volume=89 |issue=4 |pages=1522\u20137 |pmid=11007591}}</ref>\n\nIndur\u00e1in entered the Giro again, but this time was beaten by [[Evgeni Berzin]] and [[Marco Pantani]], who had prepared solely for the Giro.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/indurains-sensible-sacrifice-1585871.html|title=Indur\u00e1in's sensible sacrifice|work=The Independent |location=UK |date=11 June 1995|accessdate=16 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1994, Indur\u00e1in tested positive for [[salbutamol]] following the ''[[Tour de Picardie|Tour de L'Oise]]'' in France. Though the [[Beta2-adrenergic agonist|\u03b22-adrenergic agonist]], found in nasal inhalers, was on the controlled substances list of both the [[IOC]] and [[Union Cycliste Internationale|UCI]], both organizations permitted sportsmen with [[asthma]] to use it. However, in France there was an outright ban on its use.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/drugs-in-sport-indurain-allowed-to-use-banned-drug-1379584.html|title=Drugs in Sport: Indur\u00e1in allowed to use 'banned' drug | work=[[The Independent]] | first= | last= | date=30 August 1994 | accessdate=23 October 2010}}</ref> The IOC agreed with the UCI that Indur\u00e1in would not be punished for using a drug banned outright in France because they accepted the salbutamol was contained in a nasal inhaler he had been using legitimately to aid his respiration. In Spain, the incident was interpreted as another case of the French attempting to hinder Indur\u00e1in's domination of the sport.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/a-giant-in-the-saddle-profile-miguel-indurain-1588209.html|title=A giant in the saddle; profile; Miguel Indur\u00e1in |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=25 June 1995|accessdate=4 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== 1995: Fifth Tour victory ===\nHe also won the [[Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9]] Lib\u00e9r\u00e9 in 1995.<ref name=autogenerated10 />\n\nThe seventh stage of the [[1995 Tour de France|1995 Tour]] linked [[Charleroi]] and [[Li\u00e8ge]], both in southern Belgium. It took in the rolling roads of [[Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge]]. Indur\u00e1in attacked with [[Johan Bruyneel]] following and the rest were left 50 seconds behind. The following day Indur\u00e1in won the first time trial, organised on a demanding circuit at [[Seraing]]. Jean-Paul Ollivier wrote: \"It offered him another chance to assert his authority. Who could challenge him? The hierarchy established itself by itself. Indur\u00e1in once again set off on a demonstration Tour. This last victory by the rider from Navarra was a model of strength, intelligence and authority, all well controlled. There wasn't an tactical error, never a scare, no moments of weakness\".<ref>Ollivier, Jean-Paul (1999), Maillot Jaune, S\u00e9lection du Readers Digest, France, p82, {{ISBN|978-2-7098-1091-3}}</ref>\n\nIndur\u00e1in won the [[UCI Road World Championships&nbsp;\u2013 Men's time trial|world time trial championship]].<ref name=\"sro\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/in/miguel-indurain-1.html|title=Miguel Indur\u00e1in|publisher=Sports reference|accessdate=16 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== 1996: Aiming for sixth Tour victory ===\n[[File:Miguel Indurain.jpg|thumb|right|Miguel Indur\u00e1in in the 1996 Criterium Ciutat de L'Hospitalet]]\nHe also won the [[Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9]] Lib\u00e9r\u00e9 in 1996.<ref name=autogenerated10 />\n\nIndur\u00e1in aimed for a sixth victory in the [[1996 Tour de France|1996 Tour]], but suffered from the beginning. He came seventh in the prologue. After bronchitis in a cold and wet first week, he lost time from stage seven. He said that, on the Cormet de Roseland on 6 July, \"my legs started to feel odd but, because the speed of the group wasn't very high, I didn't take much notice. I even imagined attacking at the foot of the Arcs climbs.\"<ref name=autogenerated9>L'\u00c9quipe, France, 2 July 2004{{vs|need more bibliographic info|date=September 2014}}</ref> He dropped out of the group and lost three minutes in three kilometres. Race referees penalised him 20 seconds for accepting a bottle of drink in the last kilometre.<ref group=\"N\">Race rules forbid team managers to approach riders at the end of the race to avoid their cars interfering with the race or making it unsafe.</ref> He said the 20 seconds were nothing compared to the minute he would have lost had he not taken the bottle.<ref name=autogenerated9 /> He later said he would stop racing. The Dane [[Bjarne Riis]] won and his teammate [[Jan Ullrich]] finished second. Indur\u00e1in finished 11th and, in a stage passing through his hometown and ending in [[Pamplona]], he finished 19th, eight minutes behind the stage winner.\n\nHe won the [[Cycling at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's time trial|individual time trial]] in the [[Cycling at the 1996 Summer Olympics|1996 Olympic Games in Atlanta]], where professionals competed for the first time.<ref name=\"sro\" /> He won the title ahead of compatriot [[Abraham Olano]] and Boardman. Asked if he would trade his gold medal for a sixth Tour victory, he confirmed, saying: \"For any professional cyclist, winning the Tour is the pinnacle of their career, whereas winning the Olympic title is purely symbolic\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Benson |first1=Daniel |title=Olympic Moments: Indurain's last hurrah in Atlanta 1996 |url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/features/olympic-moments-indurains-last-hurrah-in-atlanta-1996/ |website=cyclingnews.com |accessdate=23 October 2019 |date=6 June 2012}}</ref> In the [[Cycling at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's individual road race|road race]], he finished 26th.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dufresne |first1=Chris |title=Beaten Opponents in Time Trial Left Singing Indurain |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1996-08-04-ss-31362-story.html |accessdate=23 October 2019 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=4 August 1996 |location=Atlanta}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1996, Indur\u00e1in rode the [[1996 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]] at the insistence of his team. He dropped out unexpectedly on the Mirador del Fito,<ref name=autogenerated9 /> {{convert|30|km|abbr=on}} from the end of the stage to [[Covadonga]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cossins |first1=Peter |title=Vuelta a Espana iconic stages: Indurain quits the Vuelta and racing |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/features/vuelta-a-espana-iconic-stages-indurain-quits-the-vuelta-and-racing/ |website=cyclingnews.com |accessdate=27 April 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427121150/http://www.cyclingnews.com/features/vuelta-a-espana-iconic-stages-indurain-quits-the-vuelta-and-racing/ |archivedate=27 April 2017 |date=24 August 2014 |url-status = dead|df= }}</ref> Relations with his team manager, [[Jos\u00e9 Miguel Echavarri]], had been difficult since an aborted attempt on the hour record in [[Colombia]] in October 1995.<ref name=autogenerated10 /> The two no longer speak.<ref name=autogenerated10 />\n\n== Retirement ==\nIndur\u00e1in took two months to consider his future, particularly the \u20ac4.5&nbsp;million that [[Manolo Saiz]] was said to have offered him to transfer to the ONCE team.<ref name=autogenerated9 /><ref name=autogenerated2>Cycling Weekly, UK, 11 January 1997</ref> Negotiations foundered over which races Indur\u00e1in would ride and whether Saiz would pay more.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> However, on 1 January 1997 he told 300 journalists and others in the El Toro hotel in Pamplona that he would not race again. \"This is a long and deeply meditated decision, especially as physically I'm in condition to win a sixth Tour\", he said. \"In early 1996 I decided it was time to go, and I tried to win the Tour for the last time. When I didn't, I thought the Olympics would be the perfect way of bowing out, but what happened after the Tour of Spain made me change my mind. Every year it gets harder and I think I have spent enough time in the sport. My family are waiting.\"<ref name=autogenerated2 /> After reading a prepared 30-line statement, he left without taking questions.<ref name=autogenerated9 />\n\nIndur\u00e1in now lives near [[Pamplona]] and has a house in [[Benidorm]], on the Mediterranean.<ref name=autogenerated7 /> He and his wife, Marisa, have three children.<ref name=autogenerated6 /> He founded the Miguel Indur\u00e1in Foundation in 1998 to promote sport in his home region of [[Navarra]]. He worked with the Spanish Olympic Committee to promote [[Sevilla]]'s candidature for the 2004 Olympics,<ref name=autogenerated10 /> and the [[Union Cycliste Internationale]]. He continues to ride a bike three or four times a week.<ref name=autogenerated6 /> He attends cyclotourist events such as [[L'\u00c9tape du Tour]],<ref>L'\u00c9quipe, France, 17 July 2003</ref> the Mallorca312 and the Cape Argus Pick & Pay Cycle Tour in Cape Town, South Africa.\n\n== Physical prowess ==\nAccording to the [[University of Ferrara]], who conducted tests on Indur\u00e1in, his strength came from his body's superior [[physiology]]. His blood took 7 litres of oxygen around his body per minute, compared to 3\u20134 litres for an ordinary person and 5\u20136 litres for fellow riders. His cardiac output was 50 litres a minute; a fit amateur cyclist's is about 25 litres. Indur\u00e1in's [[lung capacity]] was 7.8 litres, compared to an average of 6 litres.<ref name=autogenerated9 /> His [[pulse|resting pulse]] was as low as 28 [[Heart Rate|BPM]], compared to an average 60\u201372 bpm, which meant his heart would be less strained in the tough mountain stages.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2004/08/0820_040820_olympics_athletes.html |title=Olympic Gold Begins With Good Genes, Experts Say |first=Stefan |last=Lovgren |date=August 20, 2004 |work=National Geographic News }}</ref><ref name=\"BBC\" /> His [[VO2 max|VO<sub>2</sub> max]] was 88&nbsp;ml/kg/min; in comparison, [[Lance Armstrong]]'s was 83.8 ml/kg/min and [[Greg LeMond]]'s was more than 92&nbsp;ml/kg/min.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bikeraceinfo.com/oralhistory/lemond.html|title=Greg LeMond Professional Cycling's Talented Revolutionary|publisher=Bike Race Info|accessdate=8 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe consulted the Italian professor [[Francesco Conconi]] (famous for pioneering [[Erythropoietin|EPO]] use in sport) from 1987 and his weight dropped from {{convert|85|kg|lbs|sigfig=3|abbr=on}} to {{convert|78|kg|lbs|sigfig=3|abbr=on}} under his guidance,<ref name=autogenerated5 /><ref name=autogenerated1 /> \"changing himself into an all-round rider\", said Philippe Brunel in ''[[L'\u00c9quipe]]''.<ref name=autogenerated9 /> He was {{convert|10|kg|lbs|sigfig=2|abbr=on}} lighter than when he was a junior.<ref>Cycling Weekly, UK, 10 August 1991</ref>\n\nIndur\u00e1in was subjected to further physical testing at age 46, 14 years after his retirement, in a 2012 published study to determine age-related fitness decline. His maximal values were oxygen uptake 5.29 L/min (57.4 mL \u00b7 kg-1 \u00b7 min-1) and aerobic power output 450 W (4.88 W/kg) and was found to have seen greater changes in body composition than aerobic capacity as he weighed 92&nbsp;kg at the time. However, his absolute maximal and submaximal oxygen uptake and power output in 2012 still compared favorably with those exhibited by active professional cyclists.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mujika |first1=I\u00f1igo |title=The Cycling Physiology of Miguel Indurain 14 Years After Retirement |journal=International Journal of Sports Physiology and Performance |date=2012 |volume=7 |issue=4 |pages=397-400 |doi=10.1123/ijspp.7.4.397 |url=https://journals.humankinetics.com/doi/10.1123/ijspp.7.4.397 |accessdate=11 March 2019}}</ref>\n<!--comment out red-link image[[File:Miguel indurain 3.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Miguel Indur\u00e1in in 2006.]]-->\n\n=== Critics ===\nAlthough Indur\u00e1in, who has always denied doping, has never been banned or given a positive test for any sports-enhancing drug (with the exception of salbutamol), some remain skeptical of his achievements. Anti-doping expert Sandro Donati released information showing Indur\u00e1in and his Banesto team were clients of Dr. Francesco Conconi, who was later found to be doping many of his cyclist clients. The Banesto team confirmed it met Conconi but only to conduct [[Conconi test]]s on its cyclists.<ref>{{cite web|title=Report: Indur\u00e1in and Banesto were Conconi clients|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/report-indurain-and-banesto-were-conconi-clients|website=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|accessdate=25 February 2016}}</ref> Former [[Festina (cycling team)|Festina]] coach Antonie Vayer has also cast doubt on Indur\u00e1in's abilities, claiming only \"mutants\" could have performed at the level he did.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cossins|first1=Peter|title=Vayer casts doubt over performances of Indur\u00e1in and Jalabert|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/vayer-casts-doubt-over-performances-of-indurain-and-jalabert/|website=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|accessdate=25 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Personality ==\nIndur\u00e1in resisted comparison to Tour champions of the past and said he \"never felt superior to anyone\". He \"never had airs about himself and only reluctantly stepped into the limelight that came with the maillot jaune [yellow jersey]\", Andy Hood wrote in ''[[Procycling]]''.<ref name=autogenerated7>''Procycling'', UK, February 2008</ref>\n\nIndur\u00e1in was a man difficult to know. He was modest and quiet, \"governing his troops without ever being demanding.\"<ref name=autogenerated9 />  A Spanish journalist, frustrated that he could find nothing interesting about him, asked \"I wonder if his wife knows who this man is who sleeps beside her.\"<ref name=autogenerated9 /> A teammate, [[Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Bernard]] said: \"When he comes down for his meal, you don't even hear him move his chair.\"<ref name=autogenerated9 />\n\n''Procycling'' wrote:\n\nHis five straight Tour crowns paralleled Spain's coming of age following decades of repression under the dictatorship of General [[Francisco Franco|Franco]] and his face became a symbol of a new, more assertive Spain stepping confidently on to the European stage.<ref name=autogenerated7 />\n\nPhilippe Brunel in ''[[L'\u00c9quipe]]'' called him \"humble and sublime, taciturn some days. But who was this robotic athlete who, in his streamlined helmet and his Plexiglass visor, dominated [''domestiquait''] the time-trials like no one before him except perhaps [[Jacques Anquetil]]?\"\n\nThe magazine ''[[Cycling Weekly]]'' wrote: \"He seems to do everything very slowly, as though he is trying to conserve energy even here. His eyes blink at half-speed but the gaze from his brown eyes is steady. He looks as relaxed off the bike as he does when he is on it, but you are aware that you are in the presence of a great bike rider.\"<ref>''Cycling Weekly'', UK, Tour de France special, 1995</ref>\n\nIndur\u00e1in said the man who most impressed him was [[Pope John Paul II]], to whom he gave a yellow jersey from the Tour de France and a pink jersey from the Giro d'Italia.<ref name=autogenerated6 /> It is rare for genuine items from his cycling career to be in another's collection, as he keeps most of his clothing, equipment etc., <ref>Robinson, J. (2018, December). Collectors Bradley Wiggins: The Wiggins Collection. ''Cyclist (The Thrill of the Ride)'', (81), 104-114.</ref> making such gifts special.\n\nIndur\u00e1in is a member of the [[Laureus World Sports Awards|Laureus World Sports Academy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laureus.com/members/151|title=Miguel Indur\u00e1in&nbsp;\u2013 Laureus Academy Member|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n== Decorations ==\n* [[File:Prince of Asturias Foundation Emblem.svg|10px]] [[Prince of Asturias Award#Sports|Prince of Asturias Award for Sports]]\n* [[File:REAL ORDEN DEL M\u00c9RITO DEPORTIVO ribbon.jpg|40px]] [[Royal Order of Sports Merit|Grand Cross of the Royal Order of Sporting Merit]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boe.es/boe/dias/1993/07/22/pdfs/A22498-22498.pdf|title=Grand Cross of the Royal Order of Sporting Merit|publisher=}}</ref>\n* [[File:Order of Civil Merit (Spain) - Sash of Grand Collar.svg|40px]] [[Order of Civil Merit|Grand Cross of the Order of Civil Merit]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boe.es/diario_boe/txt.php?id=BOE-A-1995-22891|title=Grand Cross of the Order of Civil Merit \u2013 Documento BOE-A-1995-22891|website=www.boe.es}}</ref>\n* [[File:Legion Honneur Chevalier ribbon.svg|40px]] French [[Legion of Honour]]\n* [[File:Olympic Rings black.svg|30px]] [[Olympic Order]]\n\n== Career achievements ==\n===Major results===\n{{colbegin|colwidth=22em}}\n;1983\n: 1st [[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] [[Spanish National Road Race Championships|Road race]], National Amateur Road Championships\n;1984\n: 1st Stage 10 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]]) [[Tour de l'Avenir]]\n;1985\n: [[Tour de l'Avenir]]\n::1st Stages 6a & 10 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]])\n: 2nd Overall [[Vuelta a Andalucia]]\n;1986\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[Tour de l'Avenir]]\n::1st Prologue & Stage 9 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]])\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[1986 Vuelta a Murcia|Vuelta a Murcia]]\n::1st Prologue\n: 6th Overall [[Grand Prix du Midi Libre]]\n;1987\n: 1st [[GP Miguel Indur\u00e1in|GP Navarra]]\n: 1st Prologue [[1987 Vuelta a Murcia|Vuelta a Murcia]]\n: 3rd Overall [[Setmana Catalana de Ciclisme]]\n::1st [[File:Jersey green.svg|20px]] Points classification\n::1st Stages 4b ([[Individual time trial|ITT]]) & 5\n;1988\n: 1st [[File:MaillotVolta.png|20px]] Overall [[1988 Volta a Catalunya|Volta a Catalunya]]\n::1st Stage 6a ([[Individual time trial|ITT]])\n: 1st Stage 4a Vuelta a Cantabria\n: 3rd Overall [[Tour of Galicia|Vuelta a Galicia]]\n::1st Stage 2\n: 8th Overall [[Setmana Catalana de Ciclisme]]\n;1989\n: 1st [[File:Jersey white.svg|20px]] Overall [[1989 Paris\u2013Nice|Paris\u2013Nice]]\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[Crit\u00e9rium International]]\n::1st Stage 3 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]])\n: 1st Stage 9 [[1989 Tour de France|Tour de France]]\n: 7th [[1989 La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne|La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne]]\n: 10th Overall [[1989 Tour de Suisse|Tour de Suisse]]\n: 10th Overall [[1989 Volta a Catalunya|Volta a Catalunya]]\n: 10th [[1989 Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge|Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge]]\n;1990\n: 1st [[File:Jersey white.svg|20px]] Overall [[1990 Paris\u2013Nice|Paris\u2013Nice]]\n::1st Stage 6\n: 1st [[1990 Cl\u00e1sica de San Sebasti\u00e1n|Cl\u00e1sica de San Sebasti\u00e1n]]\n: 1st Stage 4 [[Vuelta a Burgos]]\n: 3rd Overall [[1990 Tour of the Basque Country|Tour of the Basque Country]]\n::1st Stage 5a\n: 3rd [[Spanish National Road Race Championships|Road race]], National Road Championships\n: 4th [[1990 La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne|La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne]]\n: 5th [[Trofeo Luis Puig]]\n: 7th Overall [[1990 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]]\n: 7th Overall [[Crit\u00e9rium International]]\n: 9th Overall [[Vuelta Ciclista a la Communidad Valenciana]]\n::1st Stage 5\n: 10th Overall [[1990 Tour de France|Tour de France]]\n::1st Stage 16\n;1991\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[1991 Tour de France|Tour de France]]\n::1st Stages 8 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]]) & 21 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]])\n: 1st [[File:MaillotVolta.png|20px]] Overall [[1991 Volta a Catalunya|Volta a Catalunya]]\n::1st Stage 5 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]])\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[Tour du Vaucluse]]\n::1st Stage 2\n: 2nd Overall [[1991 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]]\n: 3rd [[File:Bronze medal blank.svg|15px]] [[1991 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Men's road race|Road race]], [[1991 UCI Road World Championships|UCI Road World Championships]]\n: 4th [[1991 Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge|Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge]]\n;1992\n: 1st Overall [[UCI Road World Rankings]]\n: 1st [[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] [[Spanish National Road Race Championships|Road race]], National Road Championships\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[1992 Tour de France|Tour de France]]\n::1st Prologue, Stages 9 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]]) & 19 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]])\n: 1st [[File:Jersey pink.svg|20px]] Overall [[1992 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]]\n::1st [[File:Jersey blue.svg|20px]] [[Intergiro classification in the Giro d'Italia|Intergiro classification]]\n::1st Stages 3 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]]) & 21 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]])\n: 1st [[File:MaillotVolta.png|20px]] Overall [[1992 Volta a Catalunya|Volta a Catalunya]]\n: 1st Stage 1a [[Vuelta Castilla y Leon]]\n: 2nd Overall [[1992 Tour de Romandie|Tour de Romandie]]\n::1st Stage 4b ([[Individual time trial|ITT]])\n: 3rd Overall [[1992 Paris\u2013Nice|Paris\u2013Nice]]\n: 4th Overall [[Vuelta a Arag\u00f3n]]\n: 6th [[1992 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Men's road race|Road race]], [[1992 UCI Road World Championships|UCI Road World Championships]]\n;1993\n: 1st Overall [[UCI Road World Rankings]]\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[1993 Tour de France|Tour de France]]\n::1st Prologue & Stage 9 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]])\n: 1st [[File:Jersey pink.svg|20px]] Overall [[1993 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]]\n::1st Stages 10 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]]) & 19 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]])\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[Vuelta Castilla y Leon]]\n::1st Stage 1a\n: 1st Stage 6 [[1993 Vuelta a Murcia|Vuelta a Murcia]] ([[Individual time trial|ITT]])\n: 2nd [[File:Silver medal blank.svg|15px]] [[1993 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Men's road race|Road race]], [[1993 UCI Road World Championships|UCI Road World Championships]]\n: 2nd [[Spanish National Road Race Championships|Road race]], National Road Championships\n: 3rd Overall [[Vuelta Ciclista a la Communidad Valenciana]]\n;1994\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[1994 Tour de France|Tour de France]]\n::1st Stage 9 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]])\n: 1st Overall [[Tour de Picardie|Tour de l'Oise]]\n::1st Stage 4\n: 1st Stage 3 [[Vuelta Castilla y Leon]]\n: 2nd Overall [[Vuelta Ciclista a la Communidad Valenciana]]\n::1st Stage 6 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]])\n: 3rd Overall [[1994 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]]\n;1995\n: [[1995 UCI Road World Championships|UCI Road World Championships]]\n::1st [[File:Jersey rainbow chrono.svg|20px]] [[1995 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Men's time trial|Time trial]]\n::2nd [[File:Silver medal blank.svg|15px]] [[1995 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Men's road race|Road race]]\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[1995 Tour de France|Tour de France]]\n::1st Stages 8 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]]) & 19 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]])\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow-bluebar.svg|20px]] Overall [[1995 Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9|Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9]]\n::1st Stage 3 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]])\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[Grand Prix du Midi Libre]]\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[Tour of Galicia|Volta a Calicia]]\n::1st Stage 1\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[Vuelta Ciclista a La Rioja]]\n::1st Stage 1\n: 1st Stage 5a [[Vuelta a Arag\u00f3n]]\n: 3rd Overall [[Vuelta a Asturias]]\n::1st Stages 1 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]]) & 5\n: 9th [[1996 Cl\u00e1sica de San Sebasti\u00e1n|Cl\u00e1sica de San Sebasti\u00e1n]]\n;1996\n: 1st [[File:Gold medal olympic.svg|15px]] [[Cycling at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's time trial|Time trial]], [[Cycling at the 1996 Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow-bluebar.svg|20px]] Overall [[1996 Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9|Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9]]\n::1st Stages 5 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]]) & 6\n: 1st [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] Overall [[Volta ao Alentejo]]\n::1st Prologue & Stage 4\n: 1st [[File:Jersey blue.svg|20px]] Overall [[Vuelta a Asturias]]\n::1st Stage 1 ([[Individual time trial|ITT]])\n: 1st [[File:Jersey blue.svg|20px]] Overall [[Euskal Bizikleta]]\n::1st Stage 5\n: 2nd Overall [[Vuelta a Burgos]]\n{{colend}}\n\n=== Grand Tour general classification results timeline ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Grand Tour (cycling)|Grand Tour]]\n! scope=\"col\" | 1985\n! scope=\"col\" | 1986\n! scope=\"col\" | 1987\n! scope=\"col\" | 1988\n! scope=\"col\" | 1989\n! scope=\"col\" | 1990\n! scope=\"col\" | 1991\n! scope=\"col\" | 1992\n! scope=\"col\" | 1993\n! scope=\"col\" | 1994\n! scope=\"col\" | 1995\n! scope=\"col\" | 1996\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\" | [[File:Jersey pink.svg|20px|link=|alt=A pink jersey]] [[General classification in the Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]]\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|bgcolor=pink|'''[[1992 Giro d'Italia|1]]'''\n|bgcolor=pink|'''[[1993 Giro d'Italia|1]]'''\n|style=\"background:#ddf;\"| [[1994 Giro d'Italia|'''3''']]\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\" | [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px|link=|alt=A yellow jersey]] [[General classification in the Tour de France|Tour de France]]\n|[[1985 Tour de France|DNF]]\n|[[1986 Tour de France|DNF]]\n|[[1987 Tour de France|97]]\n|[[1988 Tour de France|47]]\n|[[1989 Tour de France|17]]\n|style=\"background:#ddf;\"|[[1990 Tour de France|10]]\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"|'''[[1991 Tour de France|1]]'''\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"|'''[[1992 Tour de France|1]]'''\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"|'''[[1993 Tour de France|1]]'''\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"|'''[[1994 Tour de France|1]]'''\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"|'''[[1995 Tour de France|1]]'''\n|[[1996 Tour de France|11]]\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\" | [[File:Jersey gold.svg|20px|link=|alt=A gold jersey]] [[List of Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a general classification winners|Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]]\n|[[1985 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|84]]\n|[[1986 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|92]]\n|[[1987 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|DNF]]\n|[[1988 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|DNF]]\n|[[1989 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|DNF]]\n|style=\"background:#ddf;\"|[[1990 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|7]]\n|style=\"background:#ddf;\"|'''[[1991 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|2]]'''\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|[[1996 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|DNF]]\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Legend\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \u2014\n| Did not compete\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Did Not Finish|DNF]]\n| Did not finish\n|}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=\"N\"}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|22em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book | last=Abt | first=Samuel | authorlink=Samuel Abt | others=Translated by Jeremy Munday | title=Champion: Bicycle Racing in the Age of Miguel Indur\u00e1in | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6Mz-OQAACAAJ | year=1993 | publisher=Bicycle Books | location=San Francisco | isbn=978-0-933201-59-0 }}\n* {{cite book | last=S\u00e1nchez | first=Javier Garc\u00eda | title=Indur\u00e1in: A Tempered Passion | url=https://archive.org/details/induraintempered0000garc | year=2002 | publisher=Mousehold Press | location=Norwich, UK | isbn=978-1-874739-23-4 | url-access=registration }}\n*{{cite journal |vauthors=Mujika I |title=The cycling physiology of Miguel Indur\u00e1in 14 years after retirement |journal=International Journal of Sports Physiology and Performance |volume=7 |issue=4 |pages=397\u2013400 |year=2012 |pmid=22868823 }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Miguel Indur\u00e1in}}\n* [http://www.fundacionmiguelindurain.com/ Miguel Indur\u00e1in's Foundation]\n* [http://atlanta1996.coe.es/ Spanish Olympic Committee]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{Succession box|before={{flagicon|UKR}} [[Sergey Bubka]]|title=[[Prince of Asturias Award#Sports|Prince of Asturias Award for Sports]]|years=1992|after={{flagicon|CUB}} [[Javier Sotomayor]]}}\n{{succession box\n| before=[[Kevin Young (athlete)|Kevin Young]] |\n| title=[[United Press International Athlete of the Year Award#Male winners|United Press International<br />Athlete of the Year]] |\n| after=[[Johan Olav Koss]] |\n| years=1993}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{giro d'Italia general classification winners}}\n{{Tour de France general classification winners}}\n{{V\u00e9lo d'Or}}\n{{Footer olympic champions time trial men}}\n{{UCI Road World Champions&nbsp;\u2013 Men's time trial}}\n{{Spanish Sportsman of the Year}}\n{{UCI Hall of Fame}}\n{{Prince of Asturias Award for Sports}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Indur\u00e1in, Miguel}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia cyclists]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia winners]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1984 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Navarrese cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Spain]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for Spain]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in cycling]]\n[[Category:People from Cuenca de Pamplona]]\n[[Category:Spanish male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Spanish Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Spanish Tour de France stage winners]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n[[Category:Tour de France prologue winners]]\n[[Category:Tour de France winners]]\n[[Category:UCI Road World Champions (elite men)]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia and Tour de France winners in the same year]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Pamplona]]\n", "name_user": "Nardog", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:fixingSpanish IPAperdiscussion", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miguel_Indur%C3%A1in"}
{"title_page": "Mahjong solitaire", "text_new": "{{short description|Solitaire game played with mahjong tiles}}\n{{About|the card-matching solitaire game|the Chinese tile-based game|Mahjong|other uses|Mahjong (disambiguation)}}\n\n[[File:Mahjongg Solitaire game on Ubuntu-Baltix.png|thumb|right|A Shanghai solitaire videogame arranged in \"turtle formation\"]]\n'''Mahjong solitaire''' (also known as '''Shanghai solitaire''', '''electronic''' or '''computerized mahjong''', '''solitaire mahjong''' or simply '''mahjong''') is a single-player matching game that uses a set of [[mahjong tiles]] rather than [[playing cards|cards]]. It is more commonly played on a computer than as a physical tabletop game.\n\nIts name comes from the four-player game [[mahjong]], but it is played entirely differently.\n\n==Play==\n[[Image:Mahjong solitaire-02.jpg|thumb|right|An untouched turtle formation, with exposed \"free\" tiles highlighted in blue]]\n\nThe 144 tiles are arranged in a special four-layer pattern with their faces upwards. A tile is said to be open or exposed if it can be moved either left or right without disturbing other tiles. The goal is to match open pairs of identical tiles and remove them from the board, exposing the tiles under them for play. The game is finished when all pairs of tiles have been removed from the board or when there are no exposed pairs remaining.\n\nTiles that are below other tiles cannot be seen. But by repeated undos or restarts which some programs offer, one gradually gets more and more information. Sometimes, tiles are only partially covered by other tiles, and the extent to which such tiles can be distinguished depends on the actual tile set.\n\n===Mathematical analysis===\n\nPlaying Mahjong solitaire optimally in the sense to maximize the probability of removing all tiles is [[PSPACE-complete]], and the game gets [[NP-complete]] when looking below tiles is allowed.<ref name=\"eppstein\">http://www.ics.uci.edu/~eppstein/cgt/hard.html Eppstein's page on computational complexity of games.</ref> It has been proven that it is PSPACE-hard to [[Hardness of approximation|approximate]] the maximum probability of removing all tiles within a factor of <math>n^\\epsilon</math>, assuming that there are arbitrarily many quadruples of matching tiles and that the hidden tiles are uniformly distributed.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Condon|first1=Anne|last2=Feigenbaum|first2=Joan|last3=Lund|first3=Carsten|last4=Shor|first4=Peter|title=Random debaters and the hardness of approximating stochastic functions|journal=SIAM Journal on Computing|date=1997|volume=26|issue=2|pages=369\u2013400|doi=10.1137/S0097539793260738|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/3560142_Random_Debaters_and_the_Hardness_of_Approximating_Stochastic_Functions|citeseerx=10.1.1.57.936}}</ref> The perfect-information version of this puzzle is where the player knows, before the game starts, the position of every tile. In this case, however, it is NP-complete to decide whether all tiles can be removed.<ref name=\"eppstein\" />\n\nA sample of <math>10^7</math> games with the default layout, \"the [[Turtle (Shanghai solitaire)|turtle]]\", revealed that between 2.95 and 2.96 percent of the turtles cannot be solved even if looking below tiles is allowed.<ref>http://www.math.ru.nl/~debondt/mjsolver.html Solitaire Mahjongg solver.</ref>\n\n==Variations==\n\nMahjong solitaire can be played using genuine tiles and a special wooden frame for set-up. Usually though, it is played in an electronic form as a [[computer game]]. This removes the tedium of set-up and the temptation to [[cheating|cheat]]. Some electronic Mahjong solitaire games offer extra options, such as:\n# Shuffling the tiles<ref>In these 3 the tiles can be shuffled, but not always</ref>\n# Changing the tile set and patterns from the traditional tiles to flowers, jewels or other items that may be easier to match up at a glance\n# Playing a series of different layouts with varying levels of difficulty (usually given [[Culture of China|Chinese]]-looking names such as 'the [[ox]]' or 'the [[snake]]')\n# Adding \"wildcard tiles\" and other tiles that have special functions.\n\nThese games often have a [[time limit]] which is sometimes optional. Most also offer hints or undo options which provides the ability to have a match found for the player or to backtrack and undo already made moves. Additionally, most implementations of the game arrange the tiles in such a way that the game is solvable in at least one way.\n\nMahjong solitaire can be played either solo or with a partner, in which case the aim is to accumulate the most pairs, to be the last one to match a pair, or to score the most points. Points are gained for each pair removed, with bonus points for removing matched pairs in sequence or removing pairs in sequence that are parts of sets. Using traditional mahjong tiles, the sets include the dragons, the flowers, the seasons, and the winds. The winds are usually worth the most bonus points when paired individually, but the most bonus points are achieved by matching all of the seasons followed by all of the flowers (or vice versa).\n\nWith the advent of online gaming, some computer mahjong games offer \"clash\" style player vs player challenges where each opponent solves the same board and shuffle, and the best score wins.{{fact|date=July 2019}}\n\nSome implementations offer to shuffle the tiles when there are no exposed pairs remaining, making it almost always possible for the player to complete the game.\n\n==Computer game history==\nThe computer game was originally created by [[Brodie Lockard]] in 1981 on the [[PLATO (computer system)|PLATO system]] and named ''Mah-Jongg'' after the game that uses the same tiles for play. Lockard claims that it was based on a centuries-old Chinese game called \"the Turtle\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Fregger|first=Brad|title=Lucky that way|year=1998|isbn=1-887472-56-8|pages=69\u201370}}</ref> There is a children's game in China named [[:zh:\u91e3\u91d1\u9f9c|\u62c6\u724c\u9f9c]] (\"Demolish the Tile Turtle\") of unknown age.<ref>\u7c21\u800c\u6e05\uff0c\u300a\u958b\u6aaf\u300b\uff0c1988\uff0c\u535a\u76ca\uff0c\u7b2c\u4e5d\u7248. p.151. {{ISBN|962-17-0088-4}}. Reprinted 1999\uff0c\u4e00\u672c\u5802. {{ISBN|978-962-17-4906-2}}.</ref> The computer game was released for free and was played using a CDC-721 touch screen terminal. [[Control Data Corporation]] released a new version as a paid [[online game]] in 1983. The first version remained available for free.\n\n[[File:Shisen-Sho.png|thumb|right|The [[KDE]] game ''Shisen-Sho'']]\nHowever, it was [[Activision]]'s release of ''[[Shanghai (video game)|Shanghai]]'' in 1986 for the [[IBM Personal Computer]], [[Amiga Computer]], [[Apple Macintosh|Macintosh]], [[Atari ST]] and [[Apple IIgs]] that popularised the game.{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}} The Macintosh version was created by Brodie Lockard (programming and graphics) and the Apple IIGS version was ported from the Macintosh by Ivan Manley with Brad Fregger as the producer. The game became very successful, and around 10 million copies were sold. It has been [[porting|ported]] to many different platforms. The name \"Shanghai\" was [[trademark]]ed by Activision. A similar game, known as ''Gunshy'', was also released in 1987 for the Macintosh.\n\nAs the game is based on mahjong tiles, some confusion arose with the 4-player [[mahjong]] game. Although the name ''mahjong solitaire'' is generally accepted, other names include ''The Turtle'' as well as brand names ''Shanghai Solitaire,'' ''Taipei'', ''Kyodai'' and ''[[Steve Moraff|Moraff]]'s''.\n\nA version of this game was also included in the [[Microsoft Entertainment Pack]] for [[Windows 3.x]] in 1990 and went by the name ''Taipei''. It was subsequently included in the ''[[Best of Windows Entertainment Pack]]''. Premium editions of the [[Windows Vista]] [[operating system]] and [[Windows 7]] include a version of the game known as [[Mahjong Titans]] (known in Vista build 5219 as Shanghai Solitaire).<ref>{{cite web |author=Paul Thurrott |url=http://winsupersite.com/product-review/microsoft-windows-vista-build-5219-community-technical-preview-1-review |title=Microsoft Windows Vista Build 5219 (Community Technical Preview 1) Review &#124; Product Review content from Paul Thurrott's SuperSite for Windows |publisher=Winsupersite.com |date=2010-10-06 |accessdate=2013-06-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004234639/http://winsupersite.com/product-review/microsoft-windows-vista-build-5219-community-technical-preview-1-review |archive-date=2013-10-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Video games}}\n* [[Mahjong]]\n* [[Shisen-Sho]], another solitaire game with Mahjong tiles\n* [[Crazy Quilt (solitaire)]], a solitaire card game where cards are removed from the edges of a grid\n* Other [[Solitaire]] games, especially [[Patience (game)|Patience]], or solitaire with cards\n* [[Tile-matching video game]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n<!--== External links ==\nPlease do not add links to individual Mahjong products here. Please see WP:EL and WP:SPAM to understand why. -->\n\n[[Category:Activision games]]\n[[Category:Mahjong]]\n[[Category:Mahjong video games| ]]\n[[Category:Microsoft Entertainment Pack]]\n[[Category:Microsoft games]]\n[[Category:Puzzle video games]]\n[[Category:Solitaire Mahjong tile games| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Solitaire game played with mahjong tiles}}\n{{About|the card-matching solitaire game|the Chinese tile-based Rummy game|Mahjong|other uses|Mahjong (disambiguation)}}\n\n[[File:Mahjongg Solitaire game on Ubuntu-Baltix.png|thumb|right|A Shanghai solitaire videogame arranged in \"turtle formation\"]]\n'''Mahjong solitaire''' (also known as '''Shanghai solitaire''', '''electronic''' or '''computerized mahjong''', '''solitaire mahjong''' or simply '''mahjong''') is a single-player matching game that uses a set of [[mahjong tiles]] rather than [[playing cards|cards]]. It is more commonly played on a computer than as a physical tabletop game.\n\nIts name comes from the four-player game [[mahjong]], but it is played entirely differently.\n\n==Play==\n[[Image:Mahjong solitaire-02.jpg|thumb|right|An untouched turtle formation, with exposed \"free\" tiles highlighted in blue]]\n\nThe 144 tiles are arranged in a special four-layer pattern with their faces upwards. A tile is said to be open or exposed if it can be moved either left or right without disturbing other tiles. The goal is to match open pairs of identical tiles and remove them from the board, exposing the tiles under them for play. The game is finished when all pairs of tiles have been removed from the board or when there are no exposed pairs remaining.\n\nTiles that are below other tiles cannot be seen. But by repeated undos or restarts which some programs offer, one gradually gets more and more information. Sometimes, tiles are only partially covered by other tiles, and the extent to which such tiles can be distinguished depends on the actual tile set.\n\n===Mathematical analysis===\n\nPlaying Mahjong solitaire optimally in the sense to maximize the probability of removing all tiles is [[PSPACE-complete]], and the game gets [[NP-complete]] when looking below tiles is allowed.<ref name=\"eppstein\">http://www.ics.uci.edu/~eppstein/cgt/hard.html Eppstein's page on computational complexity of games.</ref> It has been proven that it is PSPACE-hard to [[Hardness of approximation|approximate]] the maximum probability of removing all tiles within a factor of <math>n^\\epsilon</math>, assuming that there are arbitrarily many quadruples of matching tiles and that the hidden tiles are uniformly distributed.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Condon|first1=Anne|last2=Feigenbaum|first2=Joan|last3=Lund|first3=Carsten|last4=Shor|first4=Peter|title=Random debaters and the hardness of approximating stochastic functions|journal=SIAM Journal on Computing|date=1997|volume=26|issue=2|pages=369\u2013400|doi=10.1137/S0097539793260738|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/3560142_Random_Debaters_and_the_Hardness_of_Approximating_Stochastic_Functions|citeseerx=10.1.1.57.936}}</ref> The perfect-information version of this puzzle is where the player knows, before the game starts, the position of every tile. In this case, however, it is NP-complete to decide whether all tiles can be removed.<ref name=\"eppstein\" />\n\nA sample of <math>10^7</math> games with the default layout, \"the [[Turtle (Shanghai solitaire)|turtle]]\", revealed that between 2.95 and 2.96 percent of the turtles cannot be solved even if looking below tiles is allowed.<ref>http://www.math.ru.nl/~debondt/mjsolver.html Solitaire Mahjongg solver.</ref>\n\n==Variations==\n\nMahjong solitaire can be played using genuine tiles and a special wooden frame for set-up. Usually though, it is played in an electronic form as a [[computer game]]. This removes the tedium of set-up and the temptation to [[cheating|cheat]]. Some electronic Mahjong solitaire games offer extra options, such as:\n# Shuffling the tiles<ref>In these 3 the tiles can be shuffled, but not always</ref>\n# Changing the tile set and patterns from the traditional tiles to flowers, jewels or other items that may be easier to match up at a glance\n# Playing a series of different layouts with varying levels of difficulty (usually given [[Culture of China|Chinese]]-looking names such as 'the [[ox]]' or 'the [[snake]]')\n# Adding \"wildcard tiles\" and other tiles that have special functions.\n\nThese games often have a [[time limit]] which is sometimes optional. Most also offer hints or undo options which provides the ability to have a match found for the player or to backtrack and undo already made moves. Additionally, most implementations of the game arrange the tiles in such a way that the game is solvable in at least one way.\n\nMahjong solitaire can be played either solo or with a partner, in which case the aim is to accumulate the most pairs, to be the last one to match a pair, or to score the most points. Points are gained for each pair removed, with bonus points for removing matched pairs in sequence or removing pairs in sequence that are parts of sets. Using traditional mahjong tiles, the sets include the dragons, the flowers, the seasons, and the winds. The winds are usually worth the most bonus points when paired individually, but the most bonus points are achieved by matching all of the seasons followed by all of the flowers (or vice versa).\n\nWith the advent of online gaming, some computer mahjong games offer \"clash\" style player vs player challenges where each opponent solves the same board and shuffle, and the best score wins.{{fact|date=July 2019}}\n\nSome implementations offer to shuffle the tiles when there are no exposed pairs remaining, making it almost always possible for the player to complete the game.\n\n==Computer game history==\nThe computer game was originally created by [[Brodie Lockard]] in 1981 on the [[PLATO (computer system)|PLATO system]] and named ''Mah-Jongg'' after the game that uses the same tiles for play. Lockard claims that it was based on a centuries-old Chinese game called \"the Turtle\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Fregger|first=Brad|title=Lucky that way|year=1998|isbn=1-887472-56-8|pages=69\u201370}}</ref> There is a children's game in China named [[:zh:\u91e3\u91d1\u9f9c|\u62c6\u724c\u9f9c]] (\"Demolish the Tile Turtle\") of unknown age.<ref>\u7c21\u800c\u6e05\uff0c\u300a\u958b\u6aaf\u300b\uff0c1988\uff0c\u535a\u76ca\uff0c\u7b2c\u4e5d\u7248. p.151. {{ISBN|962-17-0088-4}}. Reprinted 1999\uff0c\u4e00\u672c\u5802. {{ISBN|978-962-17-4906-2}}.</ref> The computer game was released for free and was played using a CDC-721 touch screen terminal. [[Control Data Corporation]] released a new version as a paid [[online game]] in 1983. The first version remained available for free.\n\n[[File:Shisen-Sho.png|thumb|right|The [[KDE]] game ''Shisen-Sho'']]\nHowever, it was [[Activision]]'s release of ''[[Shanghai (video game)|Shanghai]]'' in 1986 for the [[IBM Personal Computer]], [[Amiga Computer]], [[Apple Macintosh|Macintosh]], [[Atari ST]] and [[Apple IIgs]] that popularised the game.{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}} The Macintosh version was created by Brodie Lockard (programming and graphics) and the Apple IIGS version was ported from the Macintosh by Ivan Manley with Brad Fregger as the producer. The game became very successful, and around 10 million copies were sold. It has been [[porting|ported]] to many different platforms. The name \"Shanghai\" was [[trademark]]ed by Activision. A similar game, known as ''Gunshy'', was also released in 1987 for the Macintosh.\n\nAs the game is based on mahjong tiles, some confusion arose with the 4-player [[mahjong]] game. Although the name ''mahjong solitaire'' is generally accepted, other names include ''The Turtle'' as well as brand names ''Shanghai Solitaire,'' ''Taipei'', ''Kyodai'' and ''[[Steve Moraff|Moraff]]'s''.\n\nA version of this game was also included in the [[Microsoft Entertainment Pack]] for [[Windows 3.x]] in 1990 and went by the name ''Taipei''. It was subsequently included in the ''[[Best of Windows Entertainment Pack]]''. Premium editions of the [[Windows Vista]] [[operating system]] and [[Windows 7]] include a version of the game known as [[Mahjong Titans]] (known in Vista build 5219 as Shanghai Solitaire).<ref>{{cite web |author=Paul Thurrott |url=http://winsupersite.com/product-review/microsoft-windows-vista-build-5219-community-technical-preview-1-review |title=Microsoft Windows Vista Build 5219 (Community Technical Preview 1) Review &#124; Product Review content from Paul Thurrott's SuperSite for Windows |publisher=Winsupersite.com |date=2010-10-06 |accessdate=2013-06-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004234639/http://winsupersite.com/product-review/microsoft-windows-vista-build-5219-community-technical-preview-1-review |archive-date=2013-10-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Video games}}\n* [[Mahjong]]\n* [[Shisen-Sho]], another solitaire game with Mahjong tiles\n* [[Crazy Quilt (solitaire)]], a solitaire card game where cards are removed from the edges of a grid\n* Other [[Solitaire]] games, especially [[Patience (game)|Patience]], or solitaire with cards\n* [[Tile-matching video game]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n<!--== External links ==\nPlease do not add links to individual Mahjong products here. Please see WP:EL and WP:SPAM to understand why. -->\n\n[[Category:Activision games]]\n[[Category:Mahjong]]\n[[Category:Mahjong video games| ]]\n[[Category:Microsoft Entertainment Pack]]\n[[Category:Microsoft games]]\n[[Category:Puzzle video games]]\n[[Category:Solitaire Mahjong tile games| ]]\n", "name_user": "ChromeGames923", "label": "safe", "comment": "about description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mahjong_solitaire"}
{"title_page": "Cipriani S.A.", "text_new": "{{redirect|Cipriani}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n'''Cipriani [[S.A. (corporation)|S.A.]]''' is an [[Italy|Italian]] hotel and leisure company domiciled in [[Luxembourg]] that owns and operates luxury restaurants and clubs around the world including [[Harry's Bar (Venice)|Harry's Bar]] in Venice and formerly the [[Rainbow Room]] in New York City. It specialises in simple, traditional Italian food.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120121014045/http://www.crestaurant.co.uk/home.php]</ref>\n\nCipriani S.A. traces its history to family patriarch Giuseppe Cipriani (1900\u20131980)\n<ref name=google-books/> who founded Harry's Bar in Venice in 1931.\nAccording to the company history, Harry Pickering, a young [[Boston]]ian, had been frequenting Hotel Europa in Venice, where Giuseppe Cipriani was a bartender. When Pickering explained that he was broke because his family had found out his drinking habits and cut him off financially, Cipriani loaned Pickering 10,000 lire (about $500 US [$7,839 in 2015 dollars]). Two years later, Pickering returned to the hotel bar, ordered a drink, and gave Cipriani 50,000 lire in return. \"Mr. Cipriani, thank you,\" he said, according to the Cipriani website. \"Here's the money. And to show you my appreciation, here's 40,000 more, enough to open a bar. We will call it Harry's Bar.\"\n\nHarry's Bar became a popular spot for celebrities like [[Ernest Hemingway]] and [[Humphrey Bogart]].  Mr. Cipriani created the  [[Bellini (cocktail)|Bellini]] cocktail there, and the food dish [[Carpaccio]] is also reputed to have originated there.\n\nGiuseppe's son Arrigo Cipriani (born 1932) is the majority owner. Arrigo is Italian for Harry.<ref name=google-books/>  His son [[Giuseppe Cipriani (racing driver)|Giuseppe Cipriani]] (born 1965) is the main business manager.\n\n==History==\n\nIn 1958 the elder Cipriani built the [[Hotel Cipriani]] in Venice.  In 1967 Cipriani Sr. sold rights to the Cipriani name trademark.<ref name=reuters-20081210/>\n\nHowever the family went international in 1985 under the Cipriani name when it opened a Harry's Bar branch in New York City in the Sherry-Netherland Hotel.<ref name=nytimes-20070801/>  Within two years the family was evicted from the hotel and opened the Cipriani Bellini bar nearby.<ref name=google-books/>  Eventually they would return to the hotel.\n[[File:Bowery-savings-bank.jpg|thumb|110 East 42nd Street]]\nIn 1997 the Ciprianis bought [[National City Bank Building|55 Wall Street]], noted for its huge ornate former [[Citigroup|First National Bank]] lobby. They sold it in 1999 and bought the [[Bowery Savings Bank]] building across from Grand Central, again noted for its huge ornate lobby.<ref name=nytimes-20060221/>  55 Wall Street Cipriani's, Grand Central Cipriani's and Cipriani Tribeca were designed by Anthony Morali of Morali Architects.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://moraliintl.com/press.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-11-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100919161157/http://moraliintl.com/press.htm |archivedate=19 September 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 1998 they leased the Rainbow Room, performed minor modification / major gutting of the 87' Rockefeller Restoration and fired the members of Local 6 of the [[Hotel Employees and Restaurant Employees Union]] which picketed it. The labor dispute was settled in 1999, resulting in a recall of the displaced Local 6 employees for 10 years until 2009, when Cipriani was evicted by the owner / operator Tishman Speyer.\n\nIn 2005 the company won a right from [[Hudson River Park]] board to develop [[Pier 57]] into Leonardo's, a luxury complex that included a museum, catering hall, shops, restaurants, a rooftop pool and a public park.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bagli|first1=Charles|title=Cipriani Wins Bid for Italian Makeover of a West Side Pier|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/04/07/nyregion/cipriani-wins-bid-for-italian-makeover-of-a-west-side-pier.html?_r=0|accessdate=18 May 2017|work=The New York Times|date=2005-04-07}}</ref>  Their principal competition was the [[Chelsea Piers]], which was just north of Pier 57.<ref name=\"nyt05\">{{cite news|last1=Bagli|first1=Charles|title=On the Waterfront, Dueling Developers; Two Visions and the Challenge of Making a Choice|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F04E3D9113BF936A35751C0A9639C8B63|accessdate=18 May 2017|work=The New York Times|date=2005-02-05}}</ref>  After winning the bid, Michael DiLeonardo, an associate of [[Peter Gotti]], turned state's evidence against the accused mobster. In his testimony DiLeonardo said the Ciprianis had paid $120,000 to the [[Gambino crime family]] to make union problems at the Rainbow Room disappear.<ref name=\"nym\">{{cite news|last1=Gray|first1=Geoffrey|title=Bellini Troubles|url=http://nymag.com/news/intelligencer/topic/62708/|accessdate=18 May 2017|work=New York Magazine|date=2009-12-13}}</ref> The charges were never confirmed. However, the Ciprianis were unsuccessful in firing the union workers. The Ciprianis relinquished their rights to develop the pier after co-investors in the project withdrew.<ref name=nytimes-20070801/><ref name=\"vil\">{{cite news|last1=Anderson|first1=Lincoln|title=Cipriani says arrivederci to Pier 57 Leonardo plan|url=http://thevillager.com/villager_158/ciprianisaysarrivederci.html|accessdate=18 May 2017|work=The Villager|date=2006-05-10}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2004 Cipriani opened in London. The site on Davies Street in Mayfair was co-founded and established by [[Fabrizio Cerina]] of Swiss banking group Credit des Alpes, who also acted as strategic advisor to Cipriani in the sale and leaseback of the Saxony Hotel, Miami in 2009, one of the biggest ever property deals in Miami.<ref>{{cite news | title =Florida hotel added to Cipriani empire | publisher =The Independent (5 February 2008) | url =https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/florida-hotel-added-to-cipriani-empire-778085.html | access-date =31 July 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 in partnership with attorney [[Steve Witkoff]], Cipriani bought 55 Wall Street again.<ref name=nytimes-20060221/>\n\nArrigio and Giuseppe pleaded guilty in 2007 to misdemeanor tax evasion for defrauding $3.5 million in state and city taxes for six years beginning in 1998. They were placed on probation through 2011 and an independent auditor was assigned to monitor future payments.<ref name=nytimes-20070801/>\n\nIn 2007 and 2008 it had a bitter dispute with the landlord L&L Holdings Company headed by David W. Levinson of the International Toy Center over its ballroom in the lobby of the landmark building in the [[Flatiron District]] at 200 Fifth Avenue and 23rd. The Ciprianis ultimately agreed to pay $12 million and vacate the building by the end of January 2009.<ref name=nypost-20080701/>\n\nIn December 2008 the High Court of England and Wales ruled that [[Orient-Express Hotels]] (which owns the Hotel Cipriani) owns the Cipriani trademark and that the use of \"Cipriani\" in the name of the London restaurant infringed its trademark rights.<ref name=reuters-20081210/><ref name=bailii-20081209/> The decision was upheld on appeal by the Court of Appeal on 24 February 2010, which ordered that the restaurant's name would have to be changed by 24 April 2010.<ref name=bailii-20100224/> The new name of the restaurant is \"C\".<ref name=cipriani-london/>\n\nIn January 2009 the Ciprianis announced plans to close the Rainbow Room in a dispute with 30 Rock owner [[Tishman Speyer Properties]]. Tishman in turn responded that it was evicting the Ciprianis from the Rainbow Room.<ref name=nytimes-20090109/>\n\n==Properties==\n;[[Venice]]\n:*[[Harry's Bar (Venice)]].<ref name=cipriani-harrysbar/>\n:*Harry's Dolci (on [[Giudecca]]).<ref name=cipriani-harrysdolci/>\n;New York City\n:*Harry Cipriani Bar, 781 Fifth Avenue.<ref name=cipriani-harrycipriani/>\n:*[[55 Wall Street]] (the family owns the building which now consists of a club,<ref name=cipriani-club55/> residence<ref name=cipriani-clubresidences/> and restaurant,<ref name=cipriani-wallstreet/>).\n:*Cipriani 42nd Street (in the former [[Bowery Savings Bank]] at [[110 East 42nd Street]]).<ref name=cipriani-42ndstreet/>\n:*Cipriano Dolci in [[Grand Central Terminal]].<ref name=cipriani-dolci/>\n:*[[Rainbow Grill]] atop [[30 Rockefeller Center]]<!--ref>http://www.cipriani.com/locations/new-york/restaurants/rainbow-grill.php</ref--> (closed June 2009)<!-- dead URL -->\n:*Cipriani 23rd Street (in the International Toy Center)<!--ref>http://www.cipriani.com/locations/new-york/events/23rd-street.php</ref--> (closed January 2009)\n:*Cipriani [[25 Broadway]], the former [[Cunard Building (New York City)]] grand hall,<ref name=seq>{{cite web|title=NYC Landmarks Re-Opening as Event Spaces|url=http://sequence-events.com/blog/index.php/2014/06/09/nyc-landmarks-re-opening-as-event-spaces/|publisher=sequence|accessdate=7 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107041819/http://sequence-events.com/blog/index.php/2014/06/09/nyc-landmarks-re-opening-as-event-spaces/|archive-date=7 November 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> which opened in October 2014\n;London\n:*C London (in [[Mayfair]]).<ref name=cipriani-london/>\n;Los Angeles\n:*Cipriani Beverly Hills (planned in 2010 in the former Tower Beverly Hills Hotel).<ref name=cipriani-losangeles/>\n;[[Ibiza]]\n:*Cipriani's Downtown & Bellini Lounge Club\n:*Booom! IBIZA\n\n;[[Porto Cervo]]\n:*Cipriani Porto Cervo.<ref name=cipriani-portocervo/>\n;Hong Kong\n:*Cipriani Hong Kong.<ref name=cipriani-hongkong/>\n;[[Miami Beach]]\n:*Cipriani Ocean Beach and Club Residences (at the [[Saxony Hotel]]).<ref name=cipriani-miami/>\n;[[Istanbul]]\n:*Cipriani Istanbul (at the [https://web.archive.org/web/20101225105309/http://www.editionhotels.com//en-us/ Edition Hotel])\n;[[Mexico]]\n:*Cipriani Mexico City\n;[[Monaco]]\n:*Cipriani Monaco\n;[[Uruguay]]\n:*Cipriani [[Punta del Este]].<ref>[http://www.elpais.com.uy/111006/pciuda-597948/ciudades/vendieron-hotel-san-rafael-en-us-30-millones/ Vendieron Hotel San Rafael en US$ 30 millones. 6 de octubre de 2011 [[El Pa\u00eds (Uruguay)|El Pa\u00eds]]]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<!-- various news sources -->\n<ref name=google-books>{{cite journal| journal = [[New York Magazine]] | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=ouMCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA64&dq=Giuseppe+Cipriani+1980#PPA64,M1 | title = Behind the Coup at Cipriani | date = 19 October 1987 | format = Google Books }}</ref>\n<ref name=reuters-20081210>{{cite news | url = https://www.reuters.com/article/rbssConsumerGoodsAndRetailNews/idUSLA11233520081210 | title = Hit London restaurant told to drop Cipriani name | work = [[Reuters]] | date = 10 December 2008 }}</ref>\n<ref name=cipriani-harrysbar>{{cite web | url = http://www.cipriani.com/locations/venice/restaurants/harrys-bar.php | title = Harry's Bar | work = cipriani.com | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110902050947/http://www.cipriani.com/locations/venice/restaurants/harrys-bar.php | archivedate = 2 September 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n<ref name=nytimes-20060221>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/21/business/businessspecial2/21cipriani.html | title = Mr. Cipriani Takes His Name to Wall Street Condominiums | work = [[The New York Times]] | date = 26 February 2006 }}</ref>\n<ref name=nytimes-20070801>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/01/nyregion/01fraud.html?_r=2&oref=slogin | title = Father and Son Restaurateurs in New York City Plead Guilty to Tax Evasion | work = The New York Times | date = 1 August 2007 }}</ref>\n<ref name=nytimes-20090109>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/10/nyregion/10rainbow.html | title = Rainbow Room\u2019s Lease Terminated | work = The New York Times | date = 9 January 2009 }}</ref>\n<ref name=nypost-20080701>{{cite news | url = http://www.nypost.com/seven/07012008/business/ciao_cipriani__lease_to_end_in_09_117984.htm | title = CIAO CIPRIANI: LEASE TO END IN '09 | work = [[New York Post]] | date = 1 July 2008 }}</ref>\n\n<!-- court cases -->\n<ref name=bailii-20081209>{{cite BAILII | litigants = Hotel Cipriani SRL & Others v Cipriani (Grosvenor Street) Ltd & Others | link =  | country =  | court = EWHC | division = Ch | year = 2008 | num = 3032 | para =  | eucase =  | parallelcite = [2009] Bus LR D81, [2009] RPC 9 | date = 9 December 2008 | courtname =  | juris =  }}</ref>\n<ref name=bailii-20100224>{{cite BAILII | litigants = Hotel Cipriani SRL & Others v Cipriani (Grosvenor Street) Ltd & Others | link =  | country =  | court = EWCA | division = Civ | year = 2010 | num = 110 | para =  | eucase =  | parallelcite = [2010] RPC 16  | date = 24 February 2010 | courtname = [[Court of Appeal of England and Wales|Court of Appeal]]  | juris =  }}</ref>\n\n<!-- cipriani.com -->\n<ref name=cipriani-london>{{cite web | url = http://www.cipriani.com/locations/london.php | title = C London | work = cipriani.com | access-date = 20 October 2010 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20101016123956/http://cipriani.com/locations/london.php | archive-date = 16 October 2010 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n<ref name=cipriani-harrysbar>{{cite web | url = http://www.cipriani.com/locations/venice/restaurants/harrys-bar.php | title = Harry's Bar | work = cipriani.com | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110902050947/http://www.cipriani.com/locations/venice/restaurants/harrys-bar.php | archivedate = 2 September 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n<ref name=cipriani-harrysdolci>{{cite web | url = http://www.cipriani.com/locations/venice/restaurants/harrys-dolci.php | title = Harry's Dolci | work = cipriani.com | access-date = 26 October 2010 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20101029102935/http://cipriani.com/locations/venice/restaurants/harrys-dolci.php | archive-date = 29 October 2010 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n<ref name=cipriani-harrycipriani>{{cite